<HEADLINE> President: Syria Serious in Pursuing Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad
said his country was serious in its pursuit of fair and
comprehensive peace to "preserve its national fundamentals."
</P>
<P>
Assad made the remarks in a message to the Syrian armed forces
on the occasion of the 54th anniversary of the founding of the
Syrian army.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the message, the Damascus Radio said "the fundamentals
are based on justice and international legitimacy. We expect the
others to share with us the desire to establish fair and
comprehensive peace and return the usurped rights and land to
their legitimate owners."
</P>
<P>
Syria advocates the establishment of genuine peace that can put
an end to occupation and aggression, and create favorable
conditions for coexistence among all parties, Assad said.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that Syria was not responsible for the missing
chances of realizing peace.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied Syria's Golan Heights in the 1967 Middle East
war. The talks between the two sides on the return of the Golan
Heights broke down in early 1996 due to the intransigence of
Israeli former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Peace is a noble goal and pressing need for the region and the
world as well, Assad said, adding "it is not us who put hurdles on
the road to this goal."
</P>
<P>
Assad reiterated that the Golan Heights would return to the
embraces of the homeland sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he underlined the parallelism of peace talks on the
Syrian and Lebanese tracks.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-styled security zone in south Lebanon, in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
