<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Turkish Claim on Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran Sunday rejected a claim made
recently by Turkish Foreign Ministry that one of the places hit
by the Turkish warplanes is located out of Iranian borders.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi expressed
regret at the claim and said Ankara tries to make false claims in
covering up its violation of Iranian air space and bombing Iranian
territory to avoid consequences.
</P>
<P>
Iran respects international borders and territory integrity
of other countries, which is part of Iran's foreign policy, the
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Ankara would be better to live up to
its legal and political obligations to compensate rather than
making baseless claims.
</P>
<P>
Iran had said that four Turkish warplanes raided the border
region of Piranshahr on July 18, killing five people and injuring
10 others.
</P>
<P>
Protesting against the bombing, Iranian Foreign Ministry
summoned the Turkish charge d'affaire to Tehran twice in a week.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a Turkish delegation toured the hit sites, a border
military post controlled by the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps
and a summer camping site of nomadic tribes. They also inspected
an unexploded missile in Piranshahr region in Iran's West
Azarbaijan province.
</P>
<P>
Following the visit, Turkish Foreign Ministry said Thursday
that one of the places hit by the Turkish warplanes is situated
out of Iranian borders.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Turkey have been in a new tension following the air
raids as Iran accused Turkey of violating its territory while
Turkey blamed Iran for supporting Turkish outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels have been fighting a guerrilla war since 1984
for an independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
