<HEADLINE> Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian Deputy Foreign Minister
Viktor Posuvalyuk died in the early hours of Sunday at the age of
59 following a protracted illness.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk graduated from the Eastern Languages Institute of
the Moscow State University and held the equivalent of a doctorate
in history.
</P>
<P>
He started diplomatic service in 1964 and worked in the Soviet
embassies in Yemen and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk served as adviser to the USSR ambassador to Syria
between 1980 and 1985. He worked for the Foreign Ministry Middle
East and North Africa Desk in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
He was Moscow's ambassador to Oman in 1990-1991 and to Iraq in
1991-1992.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk headed the Foreign Ministry Africa and Middle East
Department in the last seven years of his diplomatic career.
</P>
<P>
A versatile person, Posuvalyuk played the piano and guitar very
well and released several compact disks, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk made a significant contribution to a political
settlement around Iraq as Russian President Boris Yeltsin's
special representative, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
