<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, EU Discuss Regional Issues, Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa and his Finnish counterpart Tarja Halonen held talks on
Sunday in Alexandria on regional issues and bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on the latest developments in the Mideast
peace process, efforts exerted by the concerned parties to bring
the peace process back on track and the role of the European Union
(EU), Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Halonen arrived in the Mediterranean port city, 220 kilometers
northwest of Cairo, earlier in the day for a two-day visit within
a regional tour.
</P>
<P>
Finland is holding EU's rotating presidency for the second half
of 1999. The 15-nation European bloc desires to play a key role in
the Mideast peace process and keeps a close contact with Egypt,
the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with Israel and an
active mediator in the Arab-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Since his election in May, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
has repeatedly expressed readiness to push the peace talks with
the Palestinians forward and resume negotiations with Syria, which
came to halt in early 1996. Barak has also voiced welcome to any
efforts aimed at giving momentum to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the two foreign ministers also tackled other
regional and international issues of mutual interest, including
the situation in the Mediterranean, the Gulf and the Balkans, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa and Halonen also discussed ways of boosting their
partnership within the framework of the Barcelona process, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Barcelona process, or Euro-Med partnership, kicked off
during the 1995 conference in Barcelona, Spain, is aimed at
forging close cooperation in political coordination, economy,
trade, security and social affairs among the EU members and 12
Mediterranean countries, including Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Both Egypt and the EU have endorsed the text of their
partnership agreement after nearly four years of negotiations. The
accord provides for more open trade, coordination in many economic
and financial areas, a political dialog and joint efforts to
combat money laundering and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Halonen is also expected to meet with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
