<HEADLINE> Israel Considers Delaying Troop Withdrawal Until </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said Sunday that Israel will put off troop withdrawal from
the West Bank stipulated in an interim agreement with the
Palestinians until October 1, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Barak told a cabinet meeting that implementation of other
aspects of the U.S.-brokered Wye accord, including the release of
Palestinian political prisoners, would start by the end of August
or early September, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time Barak's timetable for the
implementation of the Wye agreement had been revealed by Israeli
media.
</P>
<P>
Since winning the May election, Barak has pledged to revive the
peace process with the Palestinians and Syria, largely frozen
under the three years of rule by his hard-line predecessor
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian track, he has committed himself to the Wye
agreement, signed and then frozen by Netanyahu late last year, but
proposed some changes to its implementation, suggesting the
combination of some parts with the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-brokered interim deal calls for Israeli withdrawal
from additional 13 percent of the West Bank in exchange for
Palestinian measures on security.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu halted the implementation of the agreement after
handing over 2 percent to the Palestinians in the first of its
three stages, citing alleged Palestinian violations.
</P>
<P>
Barak hopes the Palestinians would agree to bypass or at least
postpone for three to six months the final stage of the remaining
two phases in troop withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Barak fears the withdrawal would create sources
of friction between Israeli settlers and Palestinians since some
settlements would be isolated after the troop pullbacks, and thus
harm the chance of reaching a permanent agreement in the
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
During their summit last week, Palestinian National Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat reluctantly accepted Barak's suggestion to
consider the proposal for two weeks, but stressed that the
Palestinians would not agree to any delay and change in the
implementation.
</P>
<P>
Barak has promised that he would carry out the accord
immediately if his proposal was rejected by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have been lobbying for international support
for their positions in the past week. Both sides have called
on Washington to intervene to resolve the dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
