<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Police Set Free More Demonstrators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian police Sunday
released 44 of the 75 men who participated in an illegal
demonstration in the capital Dar es Salaam two days ago.
</P>
<P>
Regional Police Commander Alfred Gewe told reporters here
Sunday that the 44 men were freed after it was discovered that
their role in the denaturation was minimal.
</P>
<P>
Gewe said the remaining 31 man are still kept in police custody
as they are believed to be the major players in the demonstration
in Dar es Salaam Friday.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration led to an unrest in which many people in the
streets were wounded after rioters began to threw stones, bottles
and pieces of iron at the police.
</P>
<P>
To disperse rioters who were gathering around the Manyema
Mosque in the Kariakoo area, policemen fired tear gases and used
pistols, dogs and horses, seizing 75 men and 21 women.
</P>
<P>
The women, however, were released hours after they were
detained.
</P>
<P>
Gewe said the released women confessed before the law enforcers
that fundamentalists told them to wear hijab, or Moslem headscarf,
to make the event colorful and enhance the spirits of the
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Tanzanian Minister of Education and Culture Juma
Kapuya tabled a move before the National Assembly or parliament
demanding the right for Moslem girls to wear hijab in common
schools and when attending Friday prayers.
</P>
<P>
Kapuya, himself a Moslem, later withdrew the move amid concerns
of the majority of members of parliament, who claimed that
Tanzania is a secular country in which students in common schools
are supposed to wear school uniforms when attending classes.
</P>
<P>
Kapuya's change of position has caused wide protests from
Moslems and the riot was ensued.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Vice-President Omar Ali Juma urged people to maintain
peace and security in the country and guard against those who use
religious forums to fulfill their ill intentions.
</P>
<P>
Meeting sheiks and imams in Dar es Salaam, Juma said proper
procedures should be followed when people wish to present their
grievances to the government. He said Friday's demonstration was
not the best way.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the sheiks condemned the demonstration as a
hooligan affair. They said Moslems should be engaged in activities
according to the Koran.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Moslem leaders asked the government to
form a coordination body so as to enable Moslems to channel their
grievances smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president directed the Dar es Salaam regional
commander to determine who were accidentally rounded up in the
Friday demonstration and set the innocent free as soon as
possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
