<HEADLINE> Egyptian Student Given Jail Term for Claiming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Sunday threw another
person, who claimed himself a prophet, into prison, the country's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Alexandria Juveniles Criminal Court sentenced Ibrahim Sayed
Ibrahim to three years imprisonment with hard labor for contempt
of religion, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim, a 17-year-old student who was arrested at the end of
last year, was also charged with disturbing social peace and
stability by claiming himself a prophet.
</P>
<P>
His five followers were acquitted, the news agency added.
</P>
<P>
A week ago, an Alexandria court gave Ibrahim Mahfouz, a retired
civil servant, a five-year jail term for claiming to be God's
messenger and abusing religion.
</P>
<P>
Mahfouz's 21 followers were also given 1-3 years of prison
terms on charges of collaborating with him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
