<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses U.N. Committee of Impeding Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Sunday accused the
U.S. and British representatives in the U.N. Sanctions Committee
of impeding its transport contracts signed under the oil-for-food
program.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Murtadha Ahmed, Minister of Transport and Communications,
said in a statement carried by Iraqi News Agency that the
contracts concluded by his ministry are still on hold despite the
elapse of a long period since they were concluded.
</P>
<P>
These contracts provide the transport sector with spare parts
under the oil-for-food program, he said, adding that the
contracts worth very tiny sums that do not cope with the needs of
this sector.
</P>
<P>
The contracts include some spare parts and some buses, but
U.S. and British representatives in the Sanctions Committee
blocked their approval, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He said that the United Nations allocated for this sector sums
to cover needs of railways with an estimated amount of 15 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The transport sector signed a contract with the French Alstom
Company in June 1998, and one with a Chinese company to supply 80
buses in January 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly accused the U.S. and British envoys in the
U.N. Sanctions Committee of blocking or delaying the approval of
its contracts signed under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food program, now in its sixth phase which
started on May 25, Iraq is allowed to export 5.2 billion dollars
worth of oil in six months to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies for its 24 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
