<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Makes Effort to Curb TB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia is making effort to
curb the spread of tuberculosis, with 32,581 TB sufferers having
got access to direct observation treatments (Dots) over the past
seven years, an official of the Health Ministry has said.
</P>
<P>
Solomon Ketema, an expert working in National TB and Leprosy
Control Program Office, said at the weekend that 12,477 of the TB
patients got the treatment in last Ethiopian year ending July 8.
</P>
<P>
Dots, proved to be an effective way of treating TB and
recommended by the World Health Organization, was launched in
Ethiopia in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has been for years carrying out its TB and Leprosy
Control Program in major parts of the country at the cost of 13
million U.S. dollars secured from the government of Netherlands,
Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
The government is planning to popularize the program throughout
the country by 2002, the expert said, adding by that time 75
percent of the country's population will become beneficiary of the
program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
