<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Votes to Expand Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (Parliament)
Sunday approved as expected a bill presented by the coalition of
Prime Minister Ehud Barak to enlarge the cabinet from 18
ministers to 24.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset voted 68-32 to amend the legislation on government
to allow Barak to widen his cabinet, a move the prime minister
hopes will give him the broad backing he needs to accelerate peace
talks with the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
The bill secured its approval after Barak resolved a minor
dispute with one of his key coalition partners, the Shas party, by
agreeing to its demand that the party be allocated two more deputy
ministerial posts in the expansion.
</P>
<P>
The 17-seat Shas is the third largest party in the 120-member
Knesset and it has four ministers in Barak's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Since winning the May election on a platform to move forward
the Middle East peace process, Barak has managed to cobble
together a coalition that garners 75 seats in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
He has sought to expand the cabinet in an effort to satisfy his
coalition partners vying for governmental posts.
</P>
<P>
His move has raised criticism both in the opposition and his
own coalition. The critics said the government expansion would
cost tens of millions of extra shekels.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset, which begins its summer recess Monday, will
convene a special session later this week to swear in the six new
ministers and all the deputies ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
