<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2010 GMT, Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudan has categorically denied that its army is in
possession of any kinds of chemical and biological weapons,
asserting that the army has no knowledge about such weapons.
</P>
<P>
General Mohamed Osman Yassin, spokesman of the Sudanese Armed
Forces, said western media's reports on the use of such weapons by
the Sudanese Army are "absolutely false and full of fabrications,"
Sunday's Sudanese daily Al Rai Al Am reported.
(BC-Sudan-Chemical Weapons)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat met here on Sunday
with a representative of a faction opposed to the 1993 Oslo peace
accord in a bid to unite Palestinian ranks ahead of the final
status talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's meeting with Abu Ali Moustafa, the No. 2 of the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine (PFLP), was the
first since the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) led by
Arafat signed the first peace accord with Israel in 1993.
(BC-Egypt-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq's Transport and Communications Minister Ahmed
Murtadha Ahmed said Sunday that the communication stations which
were repeatedly attacked by U.S.-British warplanes are civil
stations and not military ones as the Americans claimed.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed said the civil stations that provide services to Iraqis
were severely damaged and some of the staff were killed or injured
in the strikes, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the repeated air strikes since last December led
to the break of communications between some Iraqi provinces.
(BC-Iraq-US Attacks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
