<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Restores Its First Cinema </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Albania has reopened its first
cinema, rewriting its chronicles without a cinema since the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
The new cinema, called "Millennium," was inaugurated in
downtown Tirana late Saturday afternoon after the reconstruction
of the old movie house "Republic" when Albanian President Rexhep
Meidani cut the ribbon.
</P>
<P>
The cinema, which cost the government 300,000 U.S. dollars in
reconstruction, will operate under several policies, including an
anti-pornographic rule, show of films on Sundays for children, and
introduction of Albanian films.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian Telegraphic Agency (ATA) Sunday said the movie
houses in Albania gradually disappeared since the early 1990s when
the country moved towards a private economy.
</P>
<P>
The cinemas since then have been privatized, or changed their
function, turning into clubs, game houses, store houses or other
premises, the Albanian official news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Albanian Culture Minister Edi Rama as saying
that Albania will no longer be the only country without a cinema
in the world (perhaps in Europe), although it just has one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waldner Says He Is Not A Spent Force  By Sportswriter Cao Jianjie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Never too old to
learn. Never too old to play table tennis.
</P>
<P>
Competitive table tennis is a sport for the old and experienced
more than the young and strong, said Jan-Ove Waldner, one of table
tennis oldies here bidding for a repeat of former glory.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Swede and one of all-time table tennis legends
said those over-30 guys would be forces to be reckoned with in the
world table tennis championships which opens here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Quite a few veteran players have experience, skill and strong
psyche, you'd better keep an eye on them," said the only player in the
world who has won a "Grand Slam" of Olympic, world championships and
World Cup titles.
</P>
<P>
"I feel very good because we are playing in Europe," added
Waldner. "The home-court advantage may help."
</P>
<P>
Waldner still keeps Chinese players in awe.
</P>
<P>
"Except Olympic champion Liu Guoliang who has beaten Waldner
five straight times, the Chinese players are more or less afraid of
the immensely talented Swede," said Chinese head coach Cai Zhenhua.
</P>
<P>
Waldner, who has developed an all-round game of deceptive serves
and follow-up attack, has won so many titles that he lost count.
</P>
<P>
Waldner has competed in the world championships for eight times,
on four occasions he has reached the final and twice he emerged
victorious.
</P>
<P>
Between his 1989 and 1997 world singles titles were the Olympic
gold medal in 1992, European champion in 1994 and four European Top
12 crowns.
</P>
<P>
Waldner was on Sunday drawn into the second quarter with World Cup
holder Jorg Rosskopf of Germany. If everything goes as rankings,
World No. 5 Waldner will take on No. 3 Kong Linghui of China in the
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
"My draw is not bad," said Waldner. "Rosskopf has a shoulder
problem and he is not in form, and I have a good record against
Kong."
</P>
<P>
World No. 1 Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus and South Korea's World
Cup runner-up Kim Taek Soo are bundled in the first quarter, while
two-time World Cup winner Zoran Primorac tops the third quarter. The
30-year-old Croatian will very likely fight for a semifinal berth with
Chinese upstart Wang Liqin.
</P>
<P>
The fourth quarter of the men's singles draw begins with Swedish
Jorgen Persson, 32, and ends with dual Olympic champion Liu Guoliang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Toll In India's Rail Accident Up to 250 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- At least 250 passengers were
killed and over 460 injured early Monday morning in one of the
worst rail accidents in India.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy occurred when a Delhi-bound mail train collided
head-on with an east-bound express in the wee hours Monday in
Gaisal of the Northern Siligury District of the West Bengal state.
</P>
<P>
While Indian railway officials in New Delhi confirmed 190
deaths and injuries to 310 others, reports quoted officials of the
Border Security Forces supervising rescue operations at the scene
as saying that some 200 bodies had already been extricated from
the badly Twisted remains of the two trains which collided at
01:55 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
Another 50 bodies were lying at different hospitals nearby
where the condition of over 100 injured was "serious", rescuers
and voluntary organizations reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
West Bengal Minister of State for Civil Defense Srikumar
Mukherjee, who was supervising rescue operations at the scene,
reportedly estimated that the toll might cross the 500 mark.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers feared that about 250 passengers were still trapped in
the four bogies, which could not be reached till Monday evening
due to lack of gas cutters and their precarious position and
chances of their survival were described as bleak.
</P>
<P>
Local news media said earlier Monday that at least 500 people
were feared killed and over 1,000 injured in the train mishap,
which killed four drivers of the two trains.
</P>
<P>
Railway Minister Nitish Kumar, accompanied by senior railway
officials, rushed to the site Monday and met some of the injured
passengers in nearby hospitals, according to the Press Trust of
India (PTI).
</P>
<P>
The central government has announced an ex-gratia of 25,000
rupees (581 U.S. dollars) to the next of those killed, 5,000
rupees (162 U.S. dollars) to those seriously injured and 500
rupees (11.6 U.S. dollars) to those with manor injuries.
</P>
<P>
A source in the Railway Ministry said the accident could be due
to a human error while a railway police officer said it was caused
by a signal failure.
</P>
<P>
This might be the worst railway accident that ever happened in
India in the last decade, during which over 1,500 people were
killed in some 30 tragedies.
</P>
<P>
On November 25 last year, a south-bound express train rammed
into three derailed coaches near Khanna in Ludhiana district of
the Northwest Punjab state, killing some 200 people.
</P>
<P>
The worst train accident before the latest happened in August
1995 when 302 people were killed as a Delhi-bound express train
rammed into a stationary passenger train near Firozabad in North
Uttar Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
Indian President Kocheril Raman Narayanan expressed shock
Monday over the rail accident at Gaisal and extended his heartfelt
condolences to the families of the bereaved.
</P>
<P>
PTI reported at the site that at least 14 compartments beside
the engines of both trains bore the brunt of the collision and
four compartments telescoped into each other.
</P>
<P>
The victims of the mail train were mostly army men and border
security forces, according to PTI.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports claimed that preliminary information suggested
the accident was a case of a bomb blast, but after seeing the
actual position of the engine and compartments of the trains, it
seemed to be a case of head-on collision.
</P>
<P>
The Railway Ministry announced a statutory inquiry into the
cause of the tragedy by Chief Commissioner of Railway Safety M.
Mani. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Afghan Taliban Reach Mouth of Panjsher Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's dominant Taliban
militia Monday captured Jablus Siraj and reached the mouth of the
Panjsher valley, the stronghold of the opposition forces, the
Afghan Islamic Press (AIP) agency reported.
</P>
<P>
AIP said Taliban troops were carrying out clean-up operations
around Chakikar, capital of Parwan province the militia captured
earlier Monday, and Jablus Siraj, some 70 kilometers north of
Kabul.
</P>
<P>
It said the Taliban lost five lives in the battle against 28 of
opposition forces killed and 130 taken prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Afghan analysts here said the capture of Jablus Siraj puts the
Taliban in an advantageous position to attack the Panjsher valley.
</P>
<P>
The troops loyal to former defense minister Ahmad Shah Masood
have retreated into the valley.
</P>
<P>
AIP said the Taliban forces Monday began clean-up operations in
the vast areas they captured from Masood forces who have been
pushed back some 50 kilometers from the positions they were
occupying as close as 25 kilometers from Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said that some 1,500 pieces of arms also fell
to the hands of the Islamic militia during the clean-up
operations.
</P>
<P>
Several strategic points including Nejrab, one of the seven
known entries into the Panjsher valley, and Bagram, the only air
base of the opposition forces, have fallen into the militia since
the latter launched a major offensive last Wednesday against the
Masood forces.
</P>
<P>
Another AIP report said the Taliban troops had also captured
Mahmmud-i-Raqi, capital of the northeastern province of Kapisa.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban have been waging a five-year-old war against forces
loyal to Masood who hold the northeast provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
