<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Special Fund Allocated to Flood-Hit Thai Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has decided
to allocate a 150 million baht (4.1 million U.S. dollars) special
fund for the northern province of Chantaburi which was hit by
severe flood, Channel 9, the state television, reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
So far, five people have died and another three were missing in
the flood, which was described as the worst in the province this
century.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that about 8,000 families, or around 40,000
people, in the most seriously hit Muang district have been
affected by the flooding.
</P>
<P>
Monday, Interior Minister Sanan Kachornprasart inspected the
province and distributed goods to the affected people there.
</P>
<P>
The province has been suffering from flash floods since last
Friday, when heavy rains began to pour into the province.
</P>
<P>
The provincial authorities have ordered the urgent distribution
of 10,000 packs of food and drink to people seriously affected by
the flood.
</P>
<P>
Officers have been using flat-bottomed boats to evacuate people
to safe areas, while using helicopters to reach people in remote
areas. School and temple buildings have been used as shelters for
the displaced people.
</P>
<P>
As the rain decreased Monday, the water level in the province
has receded significantly.
</P>
<P>
However, the Meteorology Department of Thailand warned that
there would be more heavy rain throughout the country over the
next couple of days.
</P>
<P>
Flash floods could happen any time in some areas of the upper
Northeastern, Eastern, and upper Southern regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
