<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Detained in Destructive Strike in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi police Monday detained
15 persons for "creating anarchy" and "damaging public property"
here during the first day of the opposition-sponsored 30-hour
nationwide destructive strike.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 riot police and paramilitary Bangladesh Rifle
forces were deployed at different important points in the capital,
and a police constable was seriously injured in the capital city
when a teargas shell bounced back from his own gun.
</P>
<P>
Barring some stray incidents, the shutdown was largely peaceful
and life was almost normal throughout the country. Most of the
government, semi-government and private offices remained open, and
rickshaws and many buses plied in the streets defying the strike,
the eighth of its kind sponsored by the opposition alliance this
year.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance, which includes the Bangladesh
Nationalist Party, the Jatiya Party, the Jamaat-e-Islami and the
Islami Oikya Jote, started the strike Monday to protest the
government's decision last week allowing "corridor to India in the
name of transshipment."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ruling Bangladesh Awami League brought out
anti-strike processions in the city protesting the 30-hour strike
enforced by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Destructive strike is very common in Bangladesh, where
opposition parties call strikes to oppose the ruling party while
the latter adopts anti-strike activities, often resulting in
clashes and causing heavy economic losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
