negotiated troop withdrawals, Prime Minister Ehud Barak said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Yugoslavia's fractious opposition plans to hold a large
rally in Belgrade on Aug. 19 to press President Slobodan Milosevic
to accept a transitional government and resign, opposition
officials said.
</P>
<P>
-- The percentage of people with Internet access who are making
purchases from Web sites declined in the second quarter of 1999
after four quarters of growth.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton pressed EU nations to take the lead in
Balkan reconstruction efforts at a summit in Sarajevo Friday.
Separately, George Robertson, the U.K. defense chief, is expected
to be named the secretary-general of NATO Monday.
</P>
<P>
-- Sun Microsystems plans to unveil a microprocessor with a
radical new architecture designed to handle complex graphics,
voice and video, in a challenge to Intel and other chip makers.
</P>
