<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Antinuclear Conferences Open in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Japan Congress Against A and H
Bombs (Gensuikin) on Monday opened a two-day international
conference in Hiroshima, western Japan, calling for efforts to
make the 21st century free of nuclear weapons and wars, the Kyodo
News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
Some 110 antinuclear advocates and academics, including 11 from
abroad, took part in the annual conference sponsored by Gensuikin,
an antinuclear group backed by Japan's Social Democratic Party (
SDP).
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Shigetoshi Iwamatsu, executive
committee chairman of the conference, said that even though
negative signs for peace are seen as Japan steps up defense
cooperation with the United States with newly enacted laws, "
discussions with people from various countries will help
strengthen movements to realize a nuclear-free world in the 21st
century."
</P>
<P>
The group called on the world to take concrete measures for
nuclear disarmament and abolition of nuclear weapons and requested
the Japanese government to take the initiative in the global
antinuclear movement.
</P>
<P>
The conference is the first of the group's series of
antinuclear events until August 9 to commemorate the 54th
anniversary of the atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in
1945.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japan's Scientists Forum of World Conference Against
A and H bomb also held its 12th annual meeting in Shizuoka,
central Japan, with some 150 people attending for talks on
scientists' roles in realizing a world free of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The forum began in 1987 and is linked with the Japan Council
Against A and H Bombs (Gensuikyo), backed by the Japanese
Communist Party (JCP). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
