<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clashing Schedules Hold Chinese Swimmers from Pan Pacs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- China had pulled out 15 swimmers
of the Pan Pacific international meeting due to the conflicting
schedules with domestic competitions, according to Chinese
swimming officials here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We reduced our line-up to five swimmers for the Pan Pacs
because of the clashing schedules," said Zhang Qiuping, spokesman
of the Chinese Swimming Association (CSA).
</P>
<P>
Zeng Qiliang, world No. 3 in the men's 100 meters breaststroke
last year, and Fu Yong, number 4 in the men's 200m backstroke on
the world rankings, will spearhead the five-member Chinese squad,
including three males and two females to the Pan Pacs from August
19 to 20.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese national team originally planned to send 20
swimmers to the two-day Pan Pacs event in Sydney, Australia, which
is the main warm-up event prior to the 2000 Olympic Games. But now
they have only five swimmers remained as the rest of the squad
were asked by their provincial associations to compete in the
National City Games.
</P>
<P>
"The National City Games, held very four years, is more
important for our provincial associations." Zhang said. "The City
Games is slated to kick off in September, just 10 days after the
Pan Pacs and the Military World Games is also in advance in the
mid August."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese National City Games, inaugurated in Shandong
Province in 1988, has made big progress in developing young
potentials across the whole country in the last decade because of
the age-limitation for its participants and the winners will bring
a lot of pride to their local associations and fans.
</P>
<P>
"Most of our swimmers who were under the age limit and
qualified for the National City Games won't compete the Pan Pacs,"
Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
While young swimmers are preparing for the City Games, elder
swimmers are concentrating on the biannual National Championships
in mid October, which is the first of the only two national
Olympic trails.
</P>
<P>
CSA had tested 326 swimmers for banned drugs through the end of
June, including 196 out-of-competition tests, and all the results
turned out negative, according to Zhang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
