<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plutonium From U.S., Russia to Remain in Canada Forever: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Surplus Plutonium from U.S. and
Russian weapons will remain forever in Canada after being used in
Ontario nuclear reactors, the Globe and Mail newspaper said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a signed memo from the Department of Foreign Affairs,
the newspaper reported that Canada will become the permanent
repository for some of the most dangerous waste products from the
nuclear-arms race, once the country starts using plutonium as fuel
in its generating stations.
</P>
<P>
This is against the backdrop where Canada has not been able to
develop a long-term storage site for atomic waste from its own
generating stations, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Under the memo written by a Canadian Foreign Affairs nuclear-
proliferation expert, Canadian officials met with their U.S.
counterparts on Canada's offer to use as fuel the weapons-grade
plutonium left over from up to 40,000 surplus nuclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
"The DOE (U.S. Department of Energy) should be advised that
this is the Canadian government position and it is also the
position of Atomic Energy of Canada Ltd. and Ontario Hydro," the
newspaper quoted the document as saying.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of plutonium in the spent weapons-grade fuel
will be 68 percent higher than regular uranium, which is usually
used by Canadian atomic plants. But reactors using the plutonium
need about 15 percent less fuel, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stepashin: Russia Against Iran Acquiring Nuke Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin said here Monday that "the acquisition of nuclear
weapons by any country, including Iran," is not in Moscow's
interests.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin made the statement following his meeting with
visiting Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who expressed concern
about the alleged "penetration of missile know-how into Iran, and
about the absence of control over this in Iraq."
</P>
<P>
"If there are any fears or suspicions that know-how which
could be used by Iran in the making of nuclear weapons is leaking
from Russia, Moscow is ready to look into these issues," the
Interfax news agency quoted Stepashin as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that his talks with Barak had been very productive. "
We understood one another and found a common language. I had the
feeling that I've known Barak for a long time. We openly
discussed the most complicated of issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We both have come to the conclusion that Russia could take a
more active part in the settlement of the Middle East situation
and in the normalization of Israeli-Syrian relations," Stepashin
said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a serious step could be taken today toward the
normalization of relations between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
"This chance must not be let slip by Israel, Syria, Russia or
the United States," said Stepashin. Barak echoed by saying that "
this chance must be taken advantage of."
</P>
<P>
Barak said Russia, a co-sponsor of the Middle East peace
process, could make a significant contribution to a Middle East
settlement.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral ties, Stepashin said the two sides have agreed to
restart the work of the Intergovernmental Trade and Economic
Commission.
</P>
<P>
In addition, an agreement concerning cooperation between the
Russian and Israeli law-enforcement agencies in the fight against
crime and terrorism has also been reached, Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who arrived here early Monday on a one-day working
visit, also met with Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
Barak said during the meeting with the Russian leaders, the
two sides had "detailed discussions on the peace process in the
Middle East and on the contribution Russia could make to the
restoration of peace in this region. We also discussed issues
pertaining to Iran and Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Barak also urged Stepashin to help find two Israeli citizens
who have gone missing in the North Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
Anti-Semitism was also a topic during the talks. "The Russian
side has assured us that it will do everything possible to curb
anti-Semitism," Barak said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
