<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Faction Rejects Offer to Join PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A major Palestinian opposition
faction has turned down Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's offer
to join the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Damascus, Syria, Maher Taher, spokesman for
the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine (PFLP), told
reporters here on Monday that Arafat has proposed that PFLP
officials take posts in the PNA.
</P>
<P>
"But we will not take part" in the Gaza-based administration,
Taher said, adding that the PFLP will not "deal with the Oslo
agreement and its consequences," referring to the 1993 peace deal
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat met here on Sunday with Abu Ali Moustafa, deputy chief
of the Damascus-based PFLP. The meeting, the first since 1993,
was aimed at ending a six-year rift over the Palestinian-Israeli
peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
The meeting ended on an upbeat note, with representatives of
both sides terming the meeting as a success and on the right path.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed to meet again in a few weeks and
decided to set up a committee comprising two members from each
side to make a list of proposals for reactivating the role of the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) and achieving Palestinian
national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
With peace hopes having revived by the election of Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, Arafat wants to make sure the divisions
within the PLO do not hamper him as he enters the final status
talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The final status talks will deal with the most difficult issues
of the peace process, including the Palestinian statehood, the
final border and refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Foreign Currency Rating Confirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 2 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's long-term
foreign currency rating of "BB" was confirmed Monday, indicating
growing faith in the country's credit-worthiness, South African
Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The international credit rating agency, Fitch IBCA, said
although, South Africa had had a difficult year in 1998, facing
large outflows of foreign capital, a sharp depreciation in the
rand and virtually no economic growth, it did manage to avoid the
sharp fall in output and rise in bad debt and bankruptcies
suffered by many other emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
"In this sense, it passed an important stress test," Fitch was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
It said there had been some recovery in both foreign confidence
and the currency this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the agency warned that the country faced even higher
unemployment and described its external debt burden as
"potentially volatile".
</P>
<P>
It also warned that the country's recovery remained vulnerable
to its low international liquidity and that the high crime level
and AIDS crisis posed serious threats to the economy.
</P>
<P>
"There may also be a return to economic growth, but
unemployment will almost certainly increase further from its
already high level.
</P>
<P>
"The incipient recovery remains vulnerable to the country's low
 international liquidity, even though short-term credit lines to
the Reserve Bank are in place.
</P>
<P>
"The Reserve Bank has also accumulated substantial uncovered
forward liabilities during its past defense of the rand, which
greatly exceed actual foreign reserves and pose a continuing risk
to market confidence, as does the high proportion of total South
African external debt, which is potentially volatile," the agency
added.
</P>
<P>
Listing South Africa's achievements, the agency said the
government had been able to reduce progressively the fiscal
deficit since 1994 and hold the government debt to GDP ratio
steady at just under 50 percent for the past four year.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing exports, which were also disappointing last year,
should benefit from the depreciation and continue to erode South
Africa's traditional over-dependence on minerals, especially gold.
The fall in the gold price, however, had not been helpful.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, South Africa under ANC (African National Congress)
rule has demonstrated that it can retain its traditional credit
strengths: a sound and well-run banking system, good physical
infrastructure, and a functioning civil legal system.
</P>
<P>
Also in the country's favor was the fact that traditional
political risks had diminished. The ANC government had proven its
political maturity through a second, successful and peaceful
parliamentary election and the smooth transition in the hand over
of power to President Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
"The government has also made significant progress in defusing
the tensions in KwaZulu-Natal and cementing the Inkatha Freedom
Party into the coalition.
</P>
<P>
"Although the ethnic mix retains the potential to cause
trouble, political extremists, both black and white, are less of a
risk.
</P>
<P>
"However, violent crime is a major fear among all sectors of
the community and a threat to social stability and inward
investment, of which South Africa requires more," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The country's short-term foreign currency rating of "B" and
long-term local currency "BBB" rating were also confirmed by the
agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Finds Evidence of Japanese Crimes Over 50 Years Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 2 (Xinhua) -- China today revealed some
materials it says prove that crimes were committed by Japan's Unit
731 during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-six volumes of materials have been made available by the
Heilongjiang provincial government to both Chinese and foreigners
to provide solid proof of Unit 731's germ warfare experiments that
used live people.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for China to make such materials
available to the public, according to Tian Ruzheng, the head of
Heilongjiang Archives. These records were selected by researchers
from the provincial archives of the years 1941 to 1944. They are
printed with the Japanese expression "special transfer", meaning
prisoners who were sent by the Japanese to Unit 731 to be for
experiments.
</P>
<P>
Unit 731 was part of Japan's Kwantung Army, whose headquarters
were in Harbin during World War II and which had a reputation for
manufacturing materials for germ warfare that were tested on live
people.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have guessed, based on confessions of Japanese war
criminals, that more than 3,000 people died from the experiments
between 1940 and 1945, but these records suggest a much larger
figure.
</P>
<P>
Judging from these records, at least 936 Chinese, Soviets,
Mongolians, and Koreans who were fighting the Japanese died as
special transfer victims in the first nine months of 1941.
</P>
<P>
The Kwantung Army headquarters burned and buried the records of
Unit 731 to get rid of evidence just before Japan surrendered on
August 15, 1945. The materials that were made public today are
just a small part of the archives that were found by accident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
