<HEADLINE> Chinese Table Tennis Players Too Powerful for Rest of World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese were so
powerful and dominant that they just lost one set on the opening day
of the world table tennis championships here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
All Chinese but a mixed doubles duo entered the second round with
straight-set victories. Only Tan Ruiwu and Zhang Yining conceded one
set in their three-set win over the Canadian combination of Johnny
Huang and Geng Lijuan in the mixed doubles opening round.
</P>
<P>
Tan, 21, and Zhang, 17, overcame mid-game setbacks to beat the
former Chinese nationals 21-18, 15-21, 21-12.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Tan Ruiwu combined with Leung Chul Seung of Hong Kong,
China, to join teammats Feng Zhe/Zhang Yong in the men's doubles
second round.
</P>
<P>
Six Chinese pairs made the women's singles second round and nine
advanced in the mixed doubles.
</P>
<P>
"We had an easy day today," said Chinese head coach Cai Zhenhua.
"We will face very strong challenge from third or fourth round."
</P>
<P>
China is bidding for a five-title sweep in the world championships,
and Cai said the men's singles event would be the most difficult.
</P>
<P>
"China and Europe are on equal footing in the men's singles event,"
Cai said. "I think at least 15 players have a chance to win this
event."
</P>
<P>
Chinese are odds-on favorites for the women's singles and doubles,
men's doubles and mixed doubles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
