<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Returning to Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Dang Qinghai, who used to
farm in China's Hebei Province, saved up more than 100,000 yuan
over the past five years from the transport business and a box
factory he ran with some partners.
</P>
<P>
With all that money he thought of having a factory of his own
but changed his mind and decided to get 50 hectares of ground for
an orchard. In explaining this surprising move, Dang says that
there is little risk and big profits in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Dang is not the only person making this move. More Chinese
farmers have returned to the land after making some money by
working in big cities or doing business far away from home. And
many are not like what they used to be before they left their
farmland years ago. Some come back to run bigger farms with better
management methods, according to the State Council's Development
Research Center.
</P>
<P>
Yang Yufang, a farmer in Hebei Province's Tanghai County,
bought a farm with 500,000 yuan that he earned from business. He
now hires college students and gets help from specialists at the
Chinese Academy of Agricultural Sciences for planting and
processing vegetables and makes a profit of nearly 200,000 yuan
annually.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the Chinese government's attempt to get
farmers to return to the land have proven effective and more
farmers have left the city where it was difficult to find a job.
The Agriculture Ministry says that about 1.8 million farmers who
had abandoned their farmland have got involved in agriculture
again, and some 200,000 have contracts to run farms or reclaim
barren hillsides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
