<HEADLINE> Arafat Accuses Israel of Evading Implementation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Palestinian National
Authority Yasser Arafat on Monday accused the Israeli government
of trying to evade the implementation of the Wye River agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader made this accusation when he was
speaking to reporters in front of his presidential premises here
upon returning from Egypt where he held talks Sunday with an
opposition Palestinian faction on Palestinian unification.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said the failure of Sunday's Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations over the implementation of Wye agreement demonstrated
Israel's attempt to avoid enforcement of the terms of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Israel must faithfully carry out all signed
agreements in order to activate the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meeting of the joint Palestinian-Israeli committee in Jerusalem
on Sunday failed to reach agreement on the implementation of the
Wye accord, and the Palestinian chief negotiator and Minister
Local Government Saeb Erekat "angrily left" the negotiating table,
Radio Israel reported Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak announced at a
cabinet meeting Sunday that Israeli redeployment in the West Bank,
in accordance with the interim Wye agreement, would begin on
October 1.
</P>
<P>
Barak had proposed to combine the last part of the Wye deal
into the more complicated final status talks with the
Palestinians, but the Palestinians rejected such idea and demanded
immediate and faithful implementation of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The United States-brokered agreement, signed last October
and then frozen by Barak's hard-line predecessor Benjamin
Netanyahu, stipulates that Israel should return another 13.1
percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
