<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Landslide, Floods Kill 15 in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The number of casualties in
Sunday's flash floods in the Philippine capital of Manila and
nearby Rizal province has risen to 15 as eight more were reported
drowned, the National Disaster Coordinating Center (NDCC) said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains, which the authorities claimed were brought
about by the much-feared La Nina phenomenon, have been pelting
Manila and nearby provinces during the past few days and Sunday's
heavy downpour that continued until Monday triggered the flash
floods.
</P>
<P>
Two of the drowned victims were from Rizal province while the
other six were from Marikina city of Metro Manila, the NDCC said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, seven persons, including a seven-month pregnant
mother, were killed in a landslide in Rizal province at dawn
Monday. The landslide fatalities came from two families, not one
as reported earlier.
</P>
<P>
It was the worst flash flood in Metro Manila and the environs
in several years in terms of casualties, said the NDCC.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado, who is also the NDCC chair,
said 8,529 families or 42,645 persons were affected by the floods
and some of them have been evacuated to higher grounds.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the authorities continued to watch on five dams in
the country's largest and most prosperous Luzon Island, as waters
were rising.
</P>
<P>
As Metro Manila was under water, lahar flows from Mt. Pinatubo,
about 100 kilometers northwest of Manila, were three to five feet
deep in the Pasig-Potrero River early Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Mercado said it would be disastrous if lahar would overflow as
Metro Manila and Rizal were already battered by flash floods.
</P>
<P>
Armed Forces Chief of Staff General Angelo Reyes has deployed
all available air, land and sea assets of the military in the
ongoing rescue operations in Metro Manila and Rizal province.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said 23 trucks, seven rubber boats and six helicopters
were in action to rescue stranded residents in flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
Some 700 people stranded in various places in Metro Manila and
Rizal due to the flash floods have been rescued.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC said the government has set up 69 evacuation centers
for the flood victims and 400 packages of relief goods have been
distributed.
</P>
<P>
Many people had to climb to the rooftop of their houses as
rampaging floodwaters surged overnight.
</P>
<P>
In many areas, the water was seven feet deep, rendering streets
impassable to all types of vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
