<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Faces Challenges of Anti-Drug Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 2 (Xinhua) -- One of the major challenges
facing the world is trafficking in illicit drugs and related
organized crimes, said Clarie Lo, commissioner for narcotics of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region government, Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the 1999 Hong Kong and
Mainland Conference on Drug Dependence, Lo said that posing a
challenge to anti-drug work would be the crisis to be brought
about by mass production of synthetic drugs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Hong Kong faces such problems as youngsters
abusing psychotropic substances at places of public entertainment
and other places, and female drug abusers.
</P>
<P>
She said Hong Kong adopted a multi-pronged approach in
combating the problems of drug trafficking and drug abuse through
law enforcement, international cooperation, treatment and
rehabilitation, preventive education and publicity, as well as
research.
</P>
<P>
Lo pointed out that Hong Kong adopted a multi-modality approach
for treatment and rehabilitation to meet the needs of drug abusers
with different backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
"This year, we'll propose legislation to require treatment and
rehabilitation centers providing voluntary residential services to
register in order to raise the standard of their services," she
added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of reported drug abusers had
been on the decrease since 1995. There were about 16,000 reported
drug abusers in 1998, and 5,527 in the first quarter of 1999,
representing a drop of 11 percent compared with the same period of
1998.
</P>
<P>
Rosanna Wong, member of the Executive Council, said that
strengthening liaison and exchanges in anti-drug work between Hong
Kong and the mainland was essential to the long term cooperation
in tackling drug problems.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that anti-drug work and latest developments in the
mainland and Hong Kong can be explored in depth at this conference,
and can benefit from your experience for further improvement to
existing services and measures," she told the participants.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Department of Psychiatry of the Chinese
University of Hong Kong, the conference features the main theme of
"Challenges and Opportunities: Multi-Modality Approach in
Substance Abuse".
</P>
<P>
Over 200 anti-drug policy administrators, law enforcers,
academics and professionals all over China attended the five-day
conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
