<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Astonished at Arafat's Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy said on Monday he was astonished that Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat had accused Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
trying to get out of some of Israel's peace commitments.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Barak last week, Arafat had agreed to
consider Israel's proposal over implementation of the Wye accord
and pledged to give an answer after two weeks, Israel Radio quoted
Levy as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Environment Minister Dalia Itzik paid a
visit to Gaza on Monday and met Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
At the start of her trip, Itzik said she had a message from
Barak to the Palestinians that Israel would carry out the Wye
accord in full if the PNA would not accept Israel's proposal of
blending part of it with the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Itzik said the new Israeli government "wanted to create a good
atmosphere in the peace talks with the PNA."
</P>
<P>
Israel and the PNA signed the Wye accord in the United States
last October, which requires Israel to hand over an additional
13.1 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin Netanyahu, hard-line predecessor of Barak, carried out
the first phase of a three-stage withdrawal, but then suspended
the accord, accusing the Palestinians of failing to fulfill their
security commitments.
</P>
<P>
After assuming office last month, Barak pledged to implement
the second stage of withdrawal, but proposed to combine the third
-stage withdrawal with the more complicated final status talks, a
stance rejected by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The sense of a crisis between the two sides emerged on Sunday
after the meeting between top Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat
and Barak's envoy and attorney Gilead Sher broke down.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians complained that Sher reiterated what Arafat
had already rejected a week earlier, while the Israeli government
complained that the Palestinians are not flexible enough. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
