<HEADLINE> Thai-Myanmar Border Check Point to Be Closed to Curb Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 2 (Xinhua) - Thailand is expected to close a
check point along the Thai-Myanmar border, which is allegedly used
as a channel to smuggle drugs from Myanmar to Thailand, Minister
of the Prime Minister's Office Jurin Laksanavisit said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Jurin, who oversees the Office of the Narcotics Control Board
(ONCB), said the San Ton Doo check point in the northern Chiang
Mai province would be temporarily shut down until the drug problem
was eased.
</P>
<P>
The decision came after Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai inspected
the area Sunday and hinted at the imminent closure.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that it is so far the government's most drastic
anti-drug action which has bilateral implications.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry is known to have been cautious over the
proposed closure, but most senior military officers, local
authorities, police, the National Security Council and the ONCB
favor the measure.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government would be informed of the closure.
According to international practice, closure of a border check
point should be agreed to by the countries which share the border.
</P>
<P>
Jurin said the check point closure was believed to help curb
the problem of drug trafficking from Myanmar, while an all-out
surveillance of Thailand's four provinces bordering Myanmar was
still needed.
</P>
<P>
The check point is adjacent to the Myanmar city of Yon,
reportedly a stronghold of the separatist United Wa State Army, a
major trafficker of amphetamines and other illicit drugs.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the National Security Council Kachadpai
Burusapatana said earlier that the check point had no substantial
economic benefits for Thailand and was a threat to national
security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
