<HEADLINE> Nets Sign Van Hron and Feick to Multi-year Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The New Jersey Nets reached
multi-year contract with their young stars Keith Van Horn and
Jamie Feick on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Keith is obviously one of the premier young players in the
league and Jamie is an emerging player," Nets general manager John
Nash said Sunday in a telephone conference call.
</P>
<P>
The Nets' leading scorer his first two years, Van Horn was
given an NBA maximum-length, six-year contract extension valued at
roughly 73 million U.S. dollars. The deal will keep him under
contract with Nets until 2006.
</P>
<P>
A 6-foot-10 power forward with the moves of a small forward,
Van Horn averaged 20.5 points and 7.4 rebounds in his first two
seasons. He averaged 19.7 points as a rookie and 21.8 last year.
</P>
<P>
Van Horn, who has had hand surgery since the end of the season,
scored 20 or more points 28 times last season and recorded a
career-high 35 points February 16 against Detroit. He shot just
under 43 percent from the field, including 30 percent from 3-point
range, and was just under 86 percent from the free-throw line,
including a streak of 48 in a row.
</P>
<P>
Feick, 25, averaged 6.3 points and 10.3 rebounds in 28 games
with New Jersey, getting the bulk of the playing time after Jayson
Williams broke his leg.
</P>
<P>
Williams has been slow in recovering from the injury, which
forced the Nets to put even greater emphasis on signing Feick.
</P>
<P>
The Nets gave Feick the middle-class exception starting at two
million U.S. dollars with annual 10 percent increases for six
years, making the deal worth about 15 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
