<HEADLINE> HKMA Grants Transfer of Restricted Banking License </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) announced Monday that it granted a transfer of
the restricted banking license of P.T. Bank Pembangunan Indonesia
(Persero) (Bapindo) to Mandiri under the Banking Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
This grant of transfer took effect on July 31, 1999, the date
on which the merger of the Legacy Banks into Mandiri became
effective in Indonesia, according to a HKMA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The transfer of the restricted banking license of Bapindo to
Mandiri enables Mandiri to continue to carry on the business
activities of the Legacy Banks in Hong Kong, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the businesses of the Legacy Banks were conducted
through the Hong Kong Branch of Bapindo and two deposit-taking
companies, namely, Staco International Finance Ltd. and Bumi Daya
International Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Established and wholly owned by the State of the Republic of
Indonesia, Mandiri is under the direct supervision of Bank
Indonesia, the banking supervisory body in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that as a restricted license bank, the Hong
Kong Branch of Mandiri (Mandiri-HK) will focus on trade financing
and corporate lending, which were the Legacy Banks' core business
activities in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The total number of restricted license banks in Hong Kong
remains unchanged, currently at 59. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
