<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine Killed as Rebels Attack Namibian Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Nine people were reportedly
killed Monday in fighting between Namibian security forces and
secessionists in Katima Mulilo, the main town of the country's
northeastern Caprivi Region, Agence France Presse reported.
</P>
<P>
Six members of the security forces and three alleged rebels
were killed earlier Monday in a gun battle at the state-owned
Namibian Broadcasting Corporation (NBC) offices. The casualties
included three soldiers and three policemen.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who entered the town after midnight, were
apparently still occupying the NBC studios by midday Monday,
Caprivi police chief Hieronymus Goraseb was quoted as saying on
radio.
</P>
<P>
They had also attempted to occupy the main police station and
an army base at the airport but had failed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers and police officers surrounding the NBC building were
not coming under fire but were prevented from entering the offices
by tear gas in the air, he said.
</P>
<P>
Namibian Defense Force Major General Martin Shalli said eight
alleged secessionists had been captured so far.
</P>
<P>
NBC spokeswoman Umbi Swartz-Karuiahe sasid in capital Windhoek:
"The police and the army are surrounding the building and are
trying to get them out using mortar bombs. This is causing heavy
damage to the property."
</P>
<P>
She said there had been no threat to NBC staff.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Katima is extremely tense and all the schools
are closed and all the streets are deserted. A colleague of mine
made a call over there and we could hear the gunshots in the
background," she said.
</P>
<P>
She was not aware if the rebels had made any broadcasts from
the station.
</P>
<P>
A Namibian Press Agency journalist, Oscar Mainga, was quoted as
saying that gunfire, which had earlier come from the town center,
had moved to the northern outskirts, towards the border with
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"The shooting is now coming from outside the town, along the
Wenela border post. We hope this is a sign the rebels are
leaving."
</P>
<P>
The Namibian Defense Force was still verifying the facts and
could not comment, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
People in the town believed the rebels were members of the
Caprivi Liberation Front, an armed secessionist movement launched
in the region last year. If their identity is confirmed, this
would be the first armed attack carried out by the group.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian government in October claimed to have uncovered a
training camp for the group seeking the secession of the Caprivi
strip, a finger of land bordered with Botswana, Zambia, Angola and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
In the security sweeps that followed, about 2,500 people,
including 15 rebel leaders, fled into neighboring Botswana, where
they were given refugee status.
</P>
<P>
Botswana insisted the separatist leaders be resettled in third
countries to avoid jeopardizing diplomatic relations with its
western neighbor. Two of the leaders of the group have already
been resettled in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
The other Namibians, who claimed to have fled Namibia for fear
of prosecution, began returning home in May.
</P>
<P>
Four of the leaders absconded from Botswana in June and were
arrested in Zambia a week later. A fifth, who disappeared from his
Botswana accommodation earlier in the year, has not been traced.
</P>
<P>
Botswana revoked the refugee status it had accorded to the five
 absconders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Save Gulf of Thailand: SEAPOL Director </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A regional environmental
organization has urged the countries bordering the Gulf of
Thailand to establish a joint mechanism to regulate the use of the
gulf in order to prevent a possible environmental catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
Thailand News Agency (TNA) Monday quoted Phipat Tangsubkul,
director of the Southeast Asian Program in Ocean Law, Policy and
Management (SEAPOL), as saying that the Gulf of Thailand is
becoming more and more polluted and fish stocks are rapidly
decreasing.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the four countries bordering it - Cambodia, Malaysia,
Thailand and Vietnam - for not taking concrete steps to prevent
these disasters.
</P>
<P>
He said all the four governments must quickly realize the
seriousness of managing the sea, and such a plan should be
implemented at the earliest date.
</P>
<P>
He urged the four countries to immediately sit down and
exchange views on how to save the sea. Otherwise, he warned that
the sea condition will deteriorate to a point when no one can
rescue it.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the four countries participated in an
informal roundtable discussion organized recently by the SEAPOL, a
non-governmental organization, in Thailand's coastal province of
Phetchaburi.
</P>
<P>
Phipat said the discussion will help the countries concerned
exchange views on the proposal and other sea-related issues.
Whether they need the joint mechanism or a mandate is up to them,
he said, but the sooner it is established the better for the
benefit of the gulf.
</P>
<P>
Although the proposal had won support from Malaysia and
Thailand, Cambodia and Vietnam were reluctant to accept it, saying
that it would certainly overlap existing mechanisms, said the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
