<HEADLINE> U.S. Destroyer Visits Japanese Civil Port Amid Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. destroyer Cushing visited
a civilian port in southwestern Japan on Monday but met protests
from local antiwar residents, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Cushing entered the port of Maizuru in Kyoto Prefecture at
around 8:30 a.m. for a five-day stopover for crew leave and
provisions.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 Japanese protesters met the vessel, chanting "We won't
cooperate in war" from land and boats.
</P>
<P>
The 9,250-ton vessel, part of the U.S. 7th Fleet, is based in
Yokosuka Naval Base in Kanagawa Prefecture. It carries Tomahawk
cruise missiles which can carry nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Ministry officials said it is the first visit
by a U.S. military vessel to a Japanese civilian port since the
new guidelines on U.S.-Japan defense cooperation were enacted in
May.
</P>
<P>
Maizuru, on the Sea of Japan coast, houses one of the five
regional headquarters of Japan's Maritime Self-Defense Force.
</P>
</TEXT>
