<HEADLINE> Major Chinese Port Cracking Down on Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, the major port for
northern China, has increased efforts to stop smuggling and
customs officers have seized 300 million yuan worth of contraband
materials in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
The Tianjing Customs Smuggling Investigation Bureau, which was
established early this year, has uncovered 18 cases of smuggling
and arrested 35 people suspected of being involved in them.
</P>
<P>
The bureau is composed of police, customs officers, and former
military personnel and has more power now and has become more
effective in dealing with smuggling, which has run rampant in the
past few years.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the bureau discovered five cases of smuggling, each
involving over 10 million yuan worth of contraband goods. 
</P>
