<HEADLINE> Share Prices Decline on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Concerns over the recent falls
on Wall Street spooked local bourse as the benchmark Straits Times
Index gave up 17.12 points to end at 2,128.65 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
The total volume was 362.33 million shares worth 491.55 million
Singapore dollars (292.78 million U.S. dollars). Falls outnumbered
rises by 207 to 112 with 126 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was a 47.66 million parcel by Delmonte which
transacted at 0.63 U.S. dollars per share. It was followed by Lian
Beng which had 15.79 million shares done. AFP was the next with
14.28 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 was the biggest gainer of the day running up 60
cents to close at 29.80 Singapore dollars. C &AMP; C and Thai Pr
picked up 30 cents to finish at 9.50 Singapore dollars and 5.50
U.S. dollars respectively. Haw Par, JIT and SIA F gained 20 cents
each to end at 3.00, 3.66 and 16.00 Singapore dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, DBS F headed the descent of the day incurring
a loss of 80 cents to close at 21.70 Singapore dollars. DBS sank
70 cents to finish at 18.40 Singapore dollars. CityDev retreated
60 cents to end at 11.10 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the decline was led by bank and property stocks,
which fell amid fears of a possible rate hike in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the market is at a delicate crossroads as it
wrestles with this problem -- the small but increasing probability
that U.S. interest rates will rise versus the large and increasing
probability that local earnings will surprise on the upside.
</P>
<P>
They said robust earnings may prevail over rate hikes. 
</P>
