<HEADLINE> Nigeria Appeals for Immediate EU Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A high ranking Nigerian official
has appealed to the European Union (EU) to resume its development
aid to his country "without further delay".
</P>
<P>
Phillip Asiodu, special economic adviser to the president made
the appeal while attending the 69th session of the African,
Caribbean and Pacific and EU Council of Ministers in Brussels, the
New Nigerian newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism that the current encouraging level of
understanding between the two partners would lead to further
strengthening of relations between them, following Nigeria's
restoring of democracy.
</P>
<P>
Asiodu told the session that the present administration was
currently on the path of achieving full re-engagement of
development cooperation between Nigeria and the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU indicated late last year that its would resume
development assistance to the west African country, which would
enable Nigeria to draw about 500 million US dollars from its
backlog of development cooperation with the union.
</P>
<P>
The organization announced the calling off of all the
restrictions in the cooperation between Nigeria and the EU days
after the west African nation's May-29 handover to civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Nigeria and the EU were severed in 1995 when
the EU imposed sanctions on Nigeria to punish the human rights
abuses of the military regime of the late Gen. Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions covered development assistance and cooperation,
military training, sales of military hardwares and other
equipment, as well as military cooperation, high level visits by
military personnel and their families, and sporting contacts.
</P>
</TEXT>
