<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Agriculture Hindered by Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A special self-sufficient
agricultural program in the besieged Huambo city in central Angola
will be endangered if seeds and fertilizer can't be transported to
the city in a few days, said an agricultural official in Huambo.
</P>
<P>
Claudio Julio, delegate of agriculture of Huambo Province, said
he is worried about the fact that agricultural materials on the
highway can't go through areas controlled by the rebel National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The authorities of the city hoped to receive seeds of potatoes,
 fertilizer and other agricultural materials through the highway
which just connected Huambo Monday with its nearest harbour city
Benguela, capital of Benguela Province.
</P>
<P>
The Huambo government put forward on June 28 a special
self-sufficient policy called Emergency Program of Agricultural
Production, deciding to resolve the deteriorating food crisis
through production. On July 15, the central government began
enacting the same program.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said transportation is the bottleneck of the new
policy. In central Angola, government troops can only station in
main cities, while UNITA rebels control vast rural areas,
attacking government convoy escorts along the highway.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Huambo are also disturbed by deteriorating seeds
imported by local government.  Local press quoted an official
source as saying that of the 15 tons of potato seeds distributed
to Caala and Calenga, four tons are completely rotten and the rest
has little capacity of germination.
</P>
<P>
The reports added that the deterioration of seeds is due to bad
 conditioning in Benguela Province, through which squads of
government soldiers escorted potato seeds to Huambo.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government imported 500 tons of potato seeds for
Huambo Province, but only 30 tons has been transported to Benguela
city.
</P>
<P>
If the agricultural materials reaches Huambo in time, the
Huambo Province is expected to harvest, in the next three month,
about 4,000 tons of potatoes, according to estimates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Calls for Int'l Cooperation in Curbing Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Foreign Minister
Lakshman Kadirgamar said Monday that the international community
should cooperate in curbing terrorism following the slaying of a
leading Tamil legislator here last week.
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar told a news conference that Sri Lanka has always
been committed to the peaceful resolution of international
conflicts as well as internal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
However, "enough mayhem and carnage has already occurred in
various countries in the last few years as a result of terrorist
activity," said Kadirgamar.
</P>
<P>
Neelan Thiruchelvam, vice-president of the moderate Tamil
United Liberation Front (TULF), was killed in a suicide bomb
attack here last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Officials confirmed that the suicide bomber was sent by the
separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) who have been
fighting for a Tamil homeland in Sri Lanka's north and east since
1983.
</P>
<P>
They said Thiruchelvam was the 36th Tamil leader killed by the
LTTE since their first high-profile assassination of then Jaffna
Mayor Alfred Duraiappa in 1975.
</P>
<P>
The assassination has provoked condemnation from U.N. Secretary
General Koffi Annan, the United States, India and others.
</P>
<P>
"In the name of the government of Sri Lanka and the people of
Sri Lanka, I earnestly seek the help of all governments to ensure
that such tragedies do not occur again," the foreign minister
said.
</P>
<P>
"Let us make the cooperation that is fast developing
internationally in the field of anti-terrorist activity a lasting
reality," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has banned the LTTE, while Britain is soon to
adopt a domestic legislation banning fund-raising for foreign
terrorist organizations like the LTTE whose overseas headquarters
is based in London. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
