<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Factions to Issue Communique on Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Two major Palestinian groups will
issue a joint communique later Monday on their first meet since
the signing of the Palestinian-Israeli peace accord in 1993,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Maher Taher, a leading member of the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine (PFLP), said here on Monday that the
delegations of PFLP and Fatah "reviewed all issues on the
Palestinian arena" during their meeting in Cairo on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Fatah, led by Arafat, is the major faction to support the peace
talks with Israel while PFLP is opposed to the Palestinian-Israeli
peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Taher said the joint communique will underline that the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) led by Yasser Arafat is
the sole representative of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
The two sides "have agreed to continue and maintain meetings,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat led the Fatah delegation to the meeting with the PFLP
delegation headed by its deputy leader Abu Ali Moustafa.
</P>
<P>
Salim al-Zanoun, a senior Fatah leader and speaker of the
Palestine National Council, called the meeting "a major success."
Al-Zanoun said the meeting called on other PLO factions and
Palestinian groups to join the unity drive.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to finalize a formula that will achieve the
Palestinian national unity," Moustafa told reporters. No matter
what differences exist between PFLP and Fatah, "what is important
is to reinvigorate the PLO," he said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Zanoun revealed that the two sides have agreed to meet again
in a few weeks and to set up a committee comprising two members
from each side to make a list of proposals for achieving
Palestinian unity and reactivating the PLO.
</P>
<P>
Arafat hopes the Fatah-PFLP meeting will be extended to include
other Palestinian factions in a bid to realize a national
reconciliation. He is scheduled to meet Nayef Hawatmeh, leader of
the Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine (DFLP) in
Cairo on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Both PFLP and DFLP, alongside six other Palestinian factions,
are based in Damascus, Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
