<HEADLINE> 1 Israeli Soldier, 2 Militiamen Wounded in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 2 (Xinhua) -- One Israeli soldier and two
members of the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA) were wounded
in a Lebanese guerrilla attack in south Lebanon, the militia's
official radio Voice of the South reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted an SLA communique as saying that the Israeli
soldier and two militiamen were hit by mortar shrapnels Sunday in
the vicinity of Beaufort Castle at the central sector of the
Israel-occupying border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
No groups has claimed responsibility for the attack, but
Israeli fighter-bombers consequently blasted suspected Hezbollah
guerrilla bases east of the southern port city of Tyre with six
air-to-surface missiles.
</P>
<P>
There were no reports of casualties from the air raids which
set plantations ablaze and shattered window glass of many houses
in the missile-hit area.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to
oust Israeli forces and SLA out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
