<HEADLINE> Brunei Opens Diplomatic Mission in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Brunei Darussalam, the tiny
oil-rich sultanate in Southeast Asia, has opened its diplomatic
mission in Bangladesh, the national news agency BSS reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Brunei's high commission started functioning at a city hotel
Sunday. This is the first time that Brunei Darussalam has opened
its mission in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Hamid ibn Abdullah, first secretary of Brunei, takes
charge of the high commission until a high commissioner is
appointed, the BSS said, quoting Foreign Ministry sources.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has been maintaining a resident mission in Brunei's
capital Bandar Seri Begawan.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad visited Brunei in May this
year, during which he held talks with leaders of the country about
opening the sultanate's mission in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Azad in early July, Brunei's Foreign Minister
Mohammed Bolkiah said that Brunei, which was desirous of
developing friendly relations and cooperation with Bangladesh, had
decided to set up its high commission in the South Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
Over 3,000 Bangladeshi nationals are employed in different
sectors of Brunei's economy and leaders of the two Muslim
countries have agreed to foster greater cooperation between them
for mutual benefit, according to the BSS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
