<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200 Confirmed Dead in India's Railway Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 people have been
confirmed dead and some 400 injured early Monday morning in one of
the worst rail accidents in India.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy occurred when a Delhi-bound mail train collided
head-on with an east-bound express in the wee hours Monday in
Gaisal of the Northern Siligury district of the West Bengal state.
</P>
<P>
While Indian railway officials here confirmed 128 deaths and
injuries to 153 others, reports quoted officials of the Border
Security Forces supervising rescue operations at the site as
saying that some 200 bodies had already been extricated from the
badly mangled remains of the two trains.
</P>
<P>
West Bengal Minister of State for Civil Defense Srikumar
Mukherjee, who was supervising rescue operations at the scene,
reportedly estimated that the toll might cross 500.
</P>
<P>
Local news media said earlier that at least 500 people were
feared killed and over 1,000 injured in the train mishap, which
killed four drivers of the two trains.
</P>
<P>
On November 25 last year, a south-bound express train rammed
into three derailed coaches near Khanna in Ludhiana district of
the Northwest Punjab state, killing some 200 people.
</P>
<P>
The worst train accident happened in August 1995 when 302
people were killed as a Delhi-bound express train rammed into a
stationary passenger train near Firozabad in North Uttar Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
Indian President Kocheril Raman Narayanan expressed shock
Monday over the rail accident at Gaisal and extended his heartfelt
condolences to the families of the bereaved.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported at the site that at
least 14 compartments beside the engines of both trains bore the
brunt of the collision and four compartments telescoped into each
other.
</P>
<P>
The victims of the mail train were mostly army men and border
security forces, according to PTI.
</P>
<P>
A local railway police officer reportedly said that preliminary
information suggested that it was a case of a bomb blast, but
after seeing the actual position of the engine and compartments of
the trains, it seemed to be a case of head-on collision due to
signal failure.
</P>
<P>
Railway Minister Nitish Kumar, who was in the east state of
Bihar, rushed back to New Delhi and is scheduled to go to the site
of the accident soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
