<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Share Prices Move Lower in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar continued falling
in Tokyo on Monday, dipping below 114 yen for the first time in
more than five months, while stock prices moved lower.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 114.02-05 yen at 5:00 p.m.
shortly after hitting the day's low of 113.95 yen, down from 114.
82-85 yen at 9:00 a.m. in Tokyo and 114.55-65 yen last Friday in
New York.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues on the First Section dropped 36.16 points to end
at 17,825.70.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 10.31 points to 1,468.62.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section thinned to an estimated 425.52
million shares, down from 511.64 million shares last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Concerns about a decline in U.S. stock prices and the
strengthening of the yen against the dollar also prevented Tokyo
investors from engaging in active purchasing, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Fujitsu was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 805 to 399, with 115 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
