<HEADLINE> Mir's Main Computer Accidentally Shut Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The main computer aboard Russia's
Mir space station was shut down accidentally last Friday,
prompting its crew to install a backup, analog computer, the
Interfax news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The computer replacement was originally scheduled for August 3
and was to take up to three days. As a result of the accident,
the work on this assignment was complete three days ahead of
schedule, Interfax said, quoting deputy mission controller Viktor
Blagov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Blagov said the space station has enough energy, although the
computer shutdown stopped the functioning of the gyros, which keep
the solar panels aligned toward the sun.
</P>
<P>
The new computer, which will be started up on Tuesday, will
control the station after the three-member crew, two Russians and
a French, left Mir for earth at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Unless new sources of funding for the station are found before
the end of the year, the 13-year-old Mir will be decommissioned
and allowed to come back to Earth to sink in a designated area in
the Pacific Ocean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
