<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Eye Nigerian Telecom Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A United States telecom company has
started investing 100 million US dollars (1.05 billion naira) in
Nigeria's telecommunication sector, signifying the start of the
expected massive inflow of foreign investment into the country.
</P>
<P>
The American satellite and telecommunication carrier Satellite
Incorporated or IDM, signed a joint venture agreement with BT
limited, a Nigeria information and communication technology
provider at San Diego, California in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The first investment is coming at a time of growing interest in
Nigeria' s telecommunications industry by the international
community, said the Guardian, newspaper Monday.
</P>
<P>
The first investment has flowed into the economy with the
installation of a VSAT Hub at the Ikoyi, Lagos head office of BT
Limited.
</P>
<P>
This investment is coming on the heels of the recently
concluded national conference on the new telecommunications
policy sponsored by the Presidency and the Ministry of
Communications which recommended full-scale liberalization of the
industry.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that foreign investment in the
telecommunication industry is expected to come in a flood when the
privatization of the Nigerian Telecommunications Limited (NITEL)
is completed and full liberalization of the sector flagged off,
expectedly, early next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
