<HEADLINE> Industrial Base In Northeast China Reports Steady Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Economy in northeast China's
Liaoning Province, an old industrial heartland, grew 6.6 percent
in the first half of this year, up 5.6 percent from the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
It had a GDP of 152 billion yuan (about 18.3 billion U.S.
dollars) for the period, with clear improvement in industrial
efficiency, according to the governor, Zhang Guoguang.
</P>
<P>
Total output value of state-owned, state-controlled and major
non-state enterprises was up 10.3 percent during the six-month
period, and losses at debt-ridden firms dropped 40 percent on a
year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
Reforms in the state sector have had some success, and 44 of
the 100 key enterprises that were running in the red had got out
of difficulties by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech and private companies saw fast-paced development
for the period. Output and profits of the high-tech sector were up
about 30 percent, and output of the private industrial sector
increased 17.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has the largest number of laid-off workers in China
and has set up re-employment centers that have helped 384,000
unemployed people and found jobs for 167,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
