<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Provides 8 Tamil MPs Special Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Eight Sri Lankan Tamil
parliamentarians have been provided special security from Monday
by the anti-terrorist unit of the police following intelligence
reports that the MPs are prime targets of Tamil rebels, informed
sources here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to intelligence reports, the eight MPs are said to be
actively canvassing support for the government's devolution
package which is expected to be presented to the House later this
month, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The anti-terrorist unit of the police has also advised the MPs
on their routes they should take when leaving and returning home
and on how they should keep changing routes, they quoted police
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) have
killed many Tamil MPs including Neelan Thiruchelvam, who was
assassinated Thursday, during the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Thiruchelvam, vice-president of the Tamil United Liberation
Front (TULF), was killed in a suicide bombing attack by the rebels
at a stone's throw from his home in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The bomber jumped off the back of a motor cyclist and onto
Thiruchelvam's car as it approached a busy intersection.
</P>
<P>
Thiruchelvam was the 36th Tamil leader killed by the LTTE since
its first assassination of then Jaffna Mayor Alfred Duraiappa in
1975.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has recently stepped up its intimidation against MPs
and public officials.
</P>
<P>
Police said intelligence reports suggested that the LTTE had
deployed a 10-member suicide squad in Colombo to assassinate
President Chandrika Kumaratunga who is believed to top the LTTE's
hit list, and several senior officials
</P>
<P>
The targets include three ministers in the cabinet, military
chiefs and a legislator from the moderate TULF, the Sunday Island
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Government troops and police have been on alert for the LTTE
rebel attacks during the whole of last month.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting a war against the Sri Lankan
government for a separate Tamil state in the north and east of the
country since 1983. About 60,000 people have been killed in the
war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
