<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Capture Key Northern City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Taliban militia Monday
captured the key northern Afghan city of Charikar after heavy
fighting with opposition Northern Alliance forces led by former
defense minister Ahmad Shah Masood, the Afghan Islamic Press (AIP)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces have also recaptured the strategic Bagram
air base which is located about 60 kilometers north of capital
Kabul, AIP quoted independent sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
At least 28 soldiers from the opposition side were killed and
many were wounded while the Taliban suffered five dead in the
fighting for Charikar, provincial capital of Parwan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban are also reported to have captured 130 opposition
fighters and seized a large quantity of arms and ammunitions in
Charikar.
</P>
<P>
According to Afghan sources, the Taliban forces are advancing
towards Jabul Saraj from Charikar. Jabul Saraj is strategically
important as it guards access to the Salang Highway that links
Kabul with northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Since the Taliban launched their summer offensive last
Wednesday, more than 1,000 people from both the warring Afghan
factions have been killed, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Sunday, the Taliban were successful in pushing the Kabul
frontlines back 25 kilometers to the southern edge of Charikar and
Bagram air base.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's summer offensive came almost immediately after
the U.N.-sponsored peace talks in Uzbekistan's capital of Tashkent
attended by representatives from Afghanistan's six neighbors plus
Russia and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
