<HEADLINE> Sino-African Economic Management Seminar For Officials Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Officials from 12 African
countries attended the opening ceremony of the 3rd Economic
Management Seminar for Officials today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Sun Guangxiang, vice-minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, told the participants that China values its economic
and trade ties with African countries. Trade with Africa was worth
5.5 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 and that economic and
technological cooperation has seen satisfactory development.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was established in 1998, based on a suggestion by
President Jiang Zemin. There had been two seminars already, from
August to September 1998, and from April to June of this year,
involving 49 government officials from 26 African countries.
</P>
<P>
During the two-month stay, participants are introduced to China
's economic developments and experiences in the opening-up policy
and its economic policies. They visit Chinese companies and attend
seminars and meetings with management, staff, and business people.
</P>
</TEXT>
