<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Keep Capital Controls: Mahathir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will continue with
its selective capital controls imposed since September 1 last
year as long as newly emerging economies remain exposed to
destructive currency trading and manipulation by the hedge funds
and currency traders as seen in the present international
financial regime, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said.
</P>
<P>
Despite repeated calls for the removal of the restriction,
Mahathir said Malaysia will lift this policy if and when currency
trading is rendered less harmful to emerging economies.
</P>
<P>
Until then the controls will remain in place and will be
defended and kept effective by whatever means that Malaysia has at
its disposal, Mahathir said in his article published by Japan's
Mainichi group of newspapers Monday, according to the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
"We are doing nobody any harm by our controls. Indeed, we are
doing a lot of good to ourselves and I venture to say, to our
trading partners, investors and even the world's economy. So I
hope we will be left to administer our own economy in our own way.
No one should tell us when we should lift the controls," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Today, Malaysia's economy is growing again. We believe it is
due to the controls we have imposed," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that currency controls imposed by Malaysia were
not generally understood by the international community and that
to understand the measures taken, one must look at the root cause
of the financial turmoil which undermined the economy of the
country.
</P>
<P>
He said the controls have apparently succeeded in bringing
about the recovery of the Malaysian economy.
</P>
<P>
Although many still condemn capital controls, others now say
that controls can solve the problems brought about by the rapid
devaluation of the currency by currency traders, and some even
recommend that other countries open to attacks by currency
speculators should adopt currency controls, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysia is now in a sound financial position,
the economy is growing and many predict it will exceed the one
percent gross domestic product (GDP) growth estimated by the
government for 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under the controls, the local currency -- the ringgit was
pegged at 3.80 per U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that even though currencies of neighboring
countries have strengthened further against the greenback and
therefore against the ringgit, Malaysia does not want to change
the exchange rate because this will upset the business
transactions and profit forecasts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
