<HEADLINE> Flash Floods Hit Central Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Flash floods caused by continuous
heavy rains hit Metro Manila and nearby provinces Sunday and
Monday, killing 10 people, inundating 11 towns and suspending
schools and government work.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the Office of Civil Defense, flash
floods caused landslide in the Cainta area of Manila Sunday night,
killing seven people of a family.
</P>
<P>
The report said three others were swept by rampaging waters and
more than 8,000 families have evacuated from their home.
</P>
<P>
Because of the widespread flooding and inclement weather in
Metro Manila, the Philippine government has suspended work in all
government offices effective 3:00 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the nearby Pampanga province, continuous rains since last
Friday destroyed a 40-meter dike of the Pampanga river and
inundated 11 towns as of Monday noon.
</P>
<P>
Floods and erosion in the province rendered some portions of
national and provincial roads impassable to all types of vehicles
and forced at least 100 persons to evacuate to safer places.
</P>
<P>
In Dagupan city in Pangasinan province, classes were suspended
in all public and private schools due to flash floods spawned by
two days of torrential rains.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada said Monday that he is
prepared to order the release of calamity funds for areas
devastated by flash floods once the National Disaster Coordinating
Council (NDCC) submits a full assessment on the extent of the
damage caused by heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
However, the president said he could not immediately declare a
state of calamity before the assessment has been submitted by the
NDCC to the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said both military and police personnel have been
placed on double alert for relief and rescue operations for the
victims of the floods.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Orlando Mercado of the Department of National Defense
said earlier that the military has sent out trucks and rubber
boats to assist families affected by the floods.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains, which the authorities claim were brought
about by the much-feared La Nina phenomenon, continued to pelt
Manila and nearby provinces during the past few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
