<HEADLINE> China Moving People From Scenic Spot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Zhangjiajie, a popular tourist
spot in the northwestern part of Hunan Province, is planning to
move some 9,000 people and a number of hotels in five years to
restore the ecological balance, an official said today.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiajie's Wulingyuan scenic area has China's first state
forest park and the Tianzi Mountain and Suoxi Valley nature
reserves on a 369-sq.km. area. Wulingyuan was added to UNESCO's
World Heritage List in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The city of Zhangjiajie was established in 1988. It has had
more than 14 million tourists, with more than two million last
year, bringing 660 million yuan (about 80 million U.S. dollars) in
revenue.
</P>
<P>
But the growth in tourism and the daily waste caused by
individuals has affected the environment, so a cleanup is
necessary. The moving of people and waste will cost about 300
million yuan (about 36.2 million dollars), according to Liu Liwei,
the secretary of the Zhangjiajie Municipal Communist Party
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Liu says that Zhangjiajie has always given priority to
environmental protection and has limited construction. In recent
years, the city has turned down more than 50 applications for
projects that could pose a threat to the environment, worth 340
million yuan (about 41 million dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Zhangjiajie has launched a campaign to replace coal and
wood with oil, gas, and electricity as fuel, and to build sewage
treatment facilities with a four-million-dollar loan from Japan
and about one million dollars of State investment.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiajie has also placed great importance on forest
protection and tree planting, Liu says, and to increase public
awareness of the ecology it has held five international forest
protection festivals since 1991. This September 21 to 27, the '99
China Eco-Tour International Forest Protection Festival will also
be held here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
