<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Rice Exports Up, Coffee Exports Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam exported more than 2.85
million tons of rice in the first seven months of this year, up 5
percent from the year-earlier period, Vietnam's English business
newspaper The Saigon Times Daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Vietnam's rice exports were busy in the first months
only. But this year Vietnam's rice shipments went steady in all
the first seven months, with July in particular seeing 450,000
tons carried abroad.
</P>
<P>
Despite the increased volume of rice exports, the average price
of rice was lower than that in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vietnam exported 315,470 tons of coffee beans worth
about 450 million U.S. dollars in the first nine months of the
1998-1999 crop, down 3.8 percent and 10.4 percent respectively
compared with the last crop.
</P>
<P>
The reduced value of export resulted from falling world prices
which pushed down Vietnam's coffee export price from 1,455 U.S.
dollars per ton in the fourth quarter of last year to 1,100
dollars per ton early last month.
</P>
<P>
Both rice and coffee are Vietnam's major export commodities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
