<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8 Million Children Facing Malnutrition in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
Monday expressed concern over the plight of more than 8 million
children under five years old who are facing malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
"We could not imagine our future leaders having poor nutrition
or facing malnutrition," the president said during a launch of the
national movement to fight malnutrition in Tangerang district,
some 40 kilometers west of here.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if the problem is left unsolved, these children
will enter the country's workforce 20 years later without any
competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
Habibie claimed that in the past 20 years, there have been rare
cases of malnutrition in the country.
</P>
<P>
The problem, he said, only arose during the onslaught of the
economic crisis in mid-1997, which weakened the people's
purchasing power, and as a result of the people's poor knowledge
on the importance of proper nutrition in raising children.
</P>
<P>
Habibie said that he is thus launching the movement to fight
malnutrition to enable people to handle the problem through four
main strategies -- the empowerment of the family, an integrated
mother-and-child health care system, inter-sectoral cooperation,
and an increase in the provision and quality of medical services.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Faried Anfasa Moeloek reported that
malnutrition has affected more than 200 of the country's 320
districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
