<HEADLINE> Telephone Charges Expected to Drop in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyans may see a drastic
reduction in the cost of international telephone calls as a
proposed regional satellite becomes reality.
</P>
<P>
The cost will go down to 10 U.S. cents per minute from the
current rate of 60 cents once the joint satellite installations
project goes operational, the weekly East African reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from Eritrea, Djibouti, Uganda, Tanzania and Kenya
attended a sub-regional meeting on the project held recently in
Nairobi, which was sponsored by the Regional Satellite
Organization (RASCOM).
</P>
<P>
According to G.D. Adadja, Director General of Abidjan-based
RASCOM, the satellite project will be implemented by a joint
venture between RASCOM and an outside partner.
</P>
<P>
Adajda noted that the joint venture between RASCOM and Alcatel
is already underway in the first stage and the project is
implemented through the build, operate and transfer venture
company.
</P>
<P>
Augustine Cheserem, Director of Telcom Kenya, told the
participants that the satellite project would provide the
improved linkages and inter- connectivity, and bring all regions
of the continent with efficient and affordable telecommunication
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The birth of Telcom Kenya reflects the restructuring of Kenya's
 telecommunication sector as stakeholders look upon the emerging
investment opportunities with considerable interest, Cheserem
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
