<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 08:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14 Brotherhood Members Arrested in Egypt: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Security forces have
arrested 14 members of the country's largest Muslim fundamentalist
group mainly on charges of violating the secular constitution.
</P>
<P>
A report carried by Egypt's Al-Akhbar daily Monday said the
State Security Investigation forces arrested the 14 men Thursday
in Giza, who belonged to the outlawed Muslim Brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Hesham Saraya of the State Security
Prosecution has ordered 13 of them be taken into custody and the
remaining one be released due to illness, the Arabic-language
newspaper said. It was not clear whether he would be charged.
</P>
<P>
The 14 men, most of whom are doctors, lawyers and engineers,
are also charged with propagating the ideas of the Muslim
Brotherhood and seeking to recruit new members, the pro-government
daily said.
</P>
<P>
These charges, including subverting the constitution, which
usually means advocating a theocratic Islamic government, are
punishable by up to 25 years in jail with hard labor.
</P>
<P>
The arrests are the latest in a largely effective four-year-old
crackdown by the Egyptian government on the Muslim Brotherhood and
other extremist Islamic groups.
</P>
<P>
Although long banned, the Brotherhood was tolerated by the
government as it was a largely peaceful movement with considerable
influence among rural Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
The government began to arrest its leaders in 1994, accusing
them of supporting Muslim militants who have been fighting
security forces in their campaign to make Egypt a strict Islamic
state.
</P>
<P>
The Brotherhood advocates an Islamic state but denies
supporting the use of violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
