<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Bank of Israel Governor Jacob Frenkel said on Sunday that
the Israeli government's intention to expand the budget deficit
is bound to increase economic instability. Frenkel also called on
the government to adopt a long-term plan to deal with inflation.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel has agreed to a three-month "reassessment" period,
during which it will abstain from pressuring on Russia over
stopping the transfer of missile technology to Iran. Meanwhile,
Prime Minister Ehud Barak is expected to meet Russian President
Boris Yeltsin in Moscow on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv
</P>
<P>
-- In a vote that will enable Barak to expand the government
without limit, Israeli Knesset (parliament) confirmed the
amendment to the Basic Law on Government Sunday by a sizable
majority. And the Knesset will meet again for a special session
during the summer recess, most likely next Monday, to confirm the
appointment of the new ministers and deputy ministers.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian sources said that the meeting between
Palestinian and Israeli negotiators over implementing the Wye
accords ended in crisis on Sunday. Meanwhile, a statement issued
by Barak's office blamed the Palestinians for not being more
flexible in peace negotiations. 
</P>
