<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A conference, organized by the World Council for
Water, will be held in Marseilles, France next Wednesday and
Thursday to discuss a long term strategy for the future of water
in the Arab states in the 21st century, Monday's Arab daily Al
Hayat reported.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An industrial delegation led by Egyptian Minister of
Industry Suleiman Reda will be visiting Baghdad during the second
half of August.
</P>
<P>
Reda will hold talks with Iraqi officials on reactivating a
1996 Egyptian-Iraqi protocol on commercial and industrial
cooperation, Al Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Abu Dhabi Commercial Bank (ADCB), the top bank in
the United Arab Emirates (UAE) with the highest net profit for
1998, is considering mergering with other banks to improve its
competitiveness, the Gulf News daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Currently the bank has 35 branches in the UAE and two overseas
branches in India.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Japan exported 20,413 automobile units to the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) in the first five months of 1999, the
Gulf News daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Car exports to the UAE from Japan during the whole of last year
were 68,170 units, according to figures from the Japanese
Automobile Manufacturers Association, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The paper said Dubai would hold an international motor show
from November 10 to 14.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman's total crude oil exports by the end of May
this year declined by 1.35 percent to 124.7 million rials (about
323.9 million U.S. dollars) from 126.4 million rials (about 328.3
million dollars) during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Oman's natural gas production increased by 16.4 percent during
the period, from 1.2 million cubic meters to 1.4 million cubic
meters, the Gulf News daily said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Revenues of Egypt's Suez Canal stood at 143.3 million
U.S. dollars in June, compared to 139.7 million dollars in the
same month last year, the country's Middle East News Agency
reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A monthly report issued by the Egyptian Cabinet Information and
Decision-support Center said Egypt's oil revenues amounted to 59
million dollars last June, as against 58 million dollars in June
last year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's foreign debts will drop to 28.2 billion
dollars by the end of 1999, Governor of the Egyptian Central Bank
Ismail Hassan said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This shows a reduction of 1.6 billion dollars due to Egypt's
punctual repayment of debts, Hassan told the country's Middle East
News Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
