<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Grateful to China for Not Devaluing Yuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad has expressed gratitude to the Chinese government
for not devaluing the Yuan (Renminbi) which he said saved East
Asian economies from a more severe financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The recovery of the East Asian economies owed a lot to this
decision by Beijing, Mahathir said in his article published by
Japan's Mainichi group of newspapers Monday, according to the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
"Had the Yuan been freely convertible, there is no doubt that
the currency traders would have attacked it and plunged China and
East Asia in an even worse turmoil and recession," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that it was not fair to expect China not to
devalue its currency forever since the devaluation of East Asian
currencies has effectively revalued upwards the Yuan and rendered
the country (China) less competitive.
</P>
<P>
"The Yuan can actually be devalued a little without affecting
the economies of the East Asian countries. But, I thank the
Chinese government for holding steadfastly to its promise not to
devalue the Yuan. China is a friend indeed, much more than some
other co-called friends," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
This is despite attempts by currency speculators to destabilize
the Chinese economy by attacking the Hong Kong Stock Exchange
(HKSE), he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Regulate Closed-End Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC)
and four other state departments issued guidelines on managing
closed-end loans today to help money-losing state-owned
enterprises get out of difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Rules on Management of Closed-end Loans provide
unified controls on qualifications, examination procedures,
management, and other aspects of closed-end loans, which target
state-owned industrial enterprises with serious losses that can
not get bank loans under normal conditions.
</P>
<P>
The closed-end loans are meant to support products that have a
market share and are profitable and the enterprises will have to
guarantee that the loans are used for purchasing, production, and
sales.
</P>
<P>
The closed-end loans are commercial loans managed in a special
way and are not policy loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
