<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Thieves Raid Ugandan Transformers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
General Manager Services Difon Okumu said here Sunday that
between 15 to 20 transformers have been burnt in Masaka District
alone by people who drain out the oil, the Monitor daily reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the problem had been tamed in the capital city,
yet it is rampant in remote districts.
</P>
<P>
Cyprian Omurangi, the electricity board's manager in the
eastern district of Mbale, has appealed to the thugs to end the
practice, saying that the general public should cooperate and wipe
out malicious and irresponsible consumers.
</P>
<P>
Over 12 homes in the district have been disconnected since the
crackdown exercise on illegal connections kicked off on July 15.
</P>
<P>
The operation has led to the recovery of 158 meters of service
cables, six single faced power meters and fuses, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The electricity board's Managing Director Paul Mare has
embarked on a crackdown exercise on illegal consumers in the
country to raise money for the company. In Kampala, arrests and
disconnections have been made to illegal consumers.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has an installed capacity of only 180 megawatts while
total estimated peak demand is 250 megawatts. This has resulted in
a power deficit of 70 megawatts leading to loadshedding which is a
constraint to investment and economic diversification.
</P>
<P>
While loadshedding in part due to a shortage of generation
capacity, it is also due to heavy technical and non-technical
losses on the distribution network and poor billing and
collection. The Ugandan power board collects revenues for only
half of power generated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
