<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 07:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Delegation Visits Syria for Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Lebanese delegation
Monday left here for Damascus to make preparatory coordination
with Syria for the anticipated resumption of peace talks with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is made up of Lebanese Foreign Ministry Director
General Zafer al Hassan and Yahya Mahmassani, diplomatic advisor
of Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will discuss with senior Syrian officials the
likely agenda topics in talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which deploys 30,000 troops in Lebanon, have
been insisting that their negotiations with Israel be conducted
simultaneously and asking Israel to return their lands without any
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured the Golan Heights from Syria in the 1967 Middle
East war and has been occupying part of south Lebanon since 1985
as a buffer zone to protect its north from Lebanese guerrillas'
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The agreement to dispatch the delegation was reached in a
telephone conversation between Hoss, who is also holding the
portfolio of foreign minister, and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk
al Sharaa last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hoss has announced that a working team has been set up to
prepare Lebanon for the seemingly impending new round of talks
with Israel's new government under Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Barak has said he would like to fully resume the peace talks
with Palestinians, Syrians and Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said the talks would probably be resumed after the Middle
East tour of United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
scheduled for this month.
</P>
<P>
He added that Lebanon's negotiating team will be formed when a
specific date is set for the negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Classical Structure In Northern China Being Repaired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, August 2 (Xinhua) -- China's Shaanxi Province has made
progress in repairing the Xiyue Temple, the province's largest
such project in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Work on the temple entrance, which was destroyed during the
Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) was completed at the end of April and
repairs on the main hall, the largest single structure in the
temple, were finished recently. Work on the Wufeng hall and two
watchtowers is going on and is expected to be completed this
winter.
</P>
<P>
The temple covers 12 ha. of land near Huashan, one of China's
sacred mountains. The central government and Shaanxi Province have
spent millions of yuan on renovation since the project began in
1994. Shaanxi plans to spend 21 million yuan over the next three
years on 14 major buildings on the temple's main axis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
