<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Situation in Indonesia's Batam Returns to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The situation in Batam,
Indonesia, returned to normal Monday after a series of clashes
which claimed dozens of lives and disrupted people's daily
activities, Antara News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The situation started to improve after the authorities deployed
some 300 security personnel to the region and Chief of the Batam
Authority Ismeth Abdullah instructed them to shoot-on-sight those
who prompted a new clash.
</P>
<P>
The communal clashes started last Thursday, following a dispute
over parking lots between two individuals from two different
ethnic groups. The clashes has led to 13 deaths and the flows of
refugees belonging to the two ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
The unrest has caused local businessmen to feel reluctant to
continue their activities in the territory, said Asman Abnur,
chairman of the provincial Chamber of Industry and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Abnur said the riot has damaged the region's image as a safe
place to invest in.
</P>
<P>
"It takes a long time to return the image after it has been
promoted to the international market," he added.
</P>
<P>
The riots also caused ferry passengers arriving at Sekupang
International Port from Singapore to drop sharply to only 5 to 10
a day.
</P>
<P>
"Visitors prefer to enter the territory through other ports
which are far from the center of the city," an official of
Sekupang port Yanuar was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Many tourists have canceled their trip to Batam and are waiting
until the situation returns to normal.
</P>
<P>
Batam, just 35 km southeast of Singapore, is a special
industrial zone and also a popular tourist destination for
Singaporeans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Establishing Website for Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's Education
Ministry is establishing an electronic website for schools
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the ministry said Monday that as part of
the New Zealand government's Information and Communication
Technologies Strategy, the establishment of the website "is a
very significant step in lifting education achievement."
</P>
<P>
Education Secretary Howard Fancy said in the release that once
the initial development is done, probably in September, "the
content will come from people who already work in the field of
education. Teachers and principals will have a very important
role."
</P>
<P>
He urged teachers and principals to tell the ministry about
what it needs to know and to improve.
</P>
<P>
"In the future, the content of the website will include
examples of good practice, materials for the seven Essential
Learning Areas of the New Zealand Curriculum and assistance with
professional development," Fancy said.
</P>
<P>
"Later on, probably within a year, we plan to develop the site
further, so it can be used by students," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
