<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Calls for Int'l Mechanism to Address Forestry Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Monday called for
an international arrangement or mechanism on forestry that covers
all types of forests to help address the inequitable situation in
the present treatment of different types of forests and overcome
the piecemeal manner in which forestry issues are now handled.
</P>
<P>
The approach to sustainable forest management must be balanced
covering all types of forests and not only tropical forests,
Malaysian Deputy Primary Industries Minister Hishammuddin Tun
Hussein said when opening here a four-day regional meeting on
sustainable forest management.
</P>
<P>
He was of the view that the present international arrangements
allowed rich temperate and boreal timber producers an open ended
schedule to implement sustainable forest management at the expense
of tropical timber producers.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that the trade in tropical timber accounts for
only a small portion of total world trade had made the situation
untenable if not grossly unjust.
</P>
<P>
"Linking global warming with deforestation of tropical forests
alone is totally unjust as tropical forests cover only seven
percent of the earth's surface while countries in the developed
world account for the major share of the world's pollution," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the solution to the two key problems of global warming
and environmental pollution cannot rest solely on the shoulders
of developing countries because the industrialized countries must
have the sincerity and political will to reduce the greenhouse
gases.
</P>
<P>
While the objective of sustainable development is noble, the
way that it is being implemented as perceived and practiced by
some countries could be counter-productive, he said, adding
counter-productive unilateral measures against tropical timber
producing countries will aggravate the situation by rendering
tropical timber less valuable thus depriving Third World tropical
timber exporters of the revenues to implement sustainable forest
management.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that critical unsolved issues include the definition
of "forests" itself, Hishammuddin said Malaysia had proposed that
the definition of forests be more comprehensive and should include
land covered with tree species besides just forest species to
include monocultural areas such as oil palm and rubber
plantations.
</P>
<P>
In the West, certain areas with single tree species were
considered as forested areas while several single tree species in
plantations in tropical countries were not, he said.
</P>
<P>
He demanded that the same recognition as given to rubber
plantations as forests by the Food and Agricultural Organization
(FAO) in its Forest Resources Assessment 2000 be also given to oil
palm plantations as they also perform similar functions as forest
species in areas of carbon sequestration, bio-diversity and the
provision of timber and non-timber products.
</P>
<P>
The regional meeting is part of a series which will later
provide inputs to the UN Conference for Sustainable Development
(UNCSD) in the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
