<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains, Floods Claim Over 30 lives in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rains since July 24 have
caused powerful floods to Vietnam's central provinces, killing
more than 30 people and making 43 others missing, local press
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some 30 people are reported dead and 43 others missing in the
flooding which swept through Vietnam's central coastal province
Binh Thuan over the last six days. Property losses are estimated
at nearly 95 billion Vietnamese dong (6.5 million U.S. dollars),
according to Vietnam's flood prevention board.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rain in the past few days, the worst in the last 20
years, has submerged around 7,500 houses and swept 178 other
houses in the province.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the floodwaters have drowned or swept away 2,400
cattle and poultry. Some 17,800 hectares of crops in the province
are under water, with crop-damage ranging from 30 percent to 100
percent. Ninety-four boats had also been sunk. Traffic on
Vietnam's National Highway 1 was halted Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The rain was measured at 490 mm in parts of the upper La Nga
River and this has been the main factor in the heavy flooding.
</P>
<P>
In Lam Dong province, floods submerged 3,500 houses, 1,000
hectares of paddy fields and 500 hectares of cashew trees in Cat
Tien District. Two people are reported killed, and more than 4,000
families have been forced to leave their houses for higher areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the residents of Daknong District in Dac Lac
province have witnessed the worst flooding in 40 years, which has
killed one person, swept away five houses and three bailey
bridges, and disrupted traffic on Highway 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
