<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Trade Surplus Increases in First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's trade surplus for
the first half of this year rose by 50.6 percent over the same
period of 1998, the Statistics Department said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The surplus increased to 33.7 billion ringgit (8.868 billion
U.S. dollars) in January-June compared with 22.4 billion ringgit
(5.894 billion dollars) a year earlier, according to statistics
released by the department.
</P>
<P>
The higher surplus was largely due to a 7.0-percent growth in
exports to 147.1 billion ringgit (38.71 billion dollars) from
137.4 billion ringgit (36.157 billion dollars) against a marginal
1.4-percent decline in imports to 113.4 billion ringgit (29.842
billion U.S. dollars) from 115.1 billion ringgit (30.289 billion
dollars), the department said.
</P>
<P>
However, the surplus in June, though the 20th consecutive month
for the country to chalk up a trade surplus since November 1997,
was 11.1 percent down to 5.4 billion ringgit (1.421 billion
dollars) from 6.1 billion ringgit (1.605 billion dollars) in the
same month last year due to a higher growth of 20.1 percent in
imports against a growth of 12 percent in exports, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
