<HEADLINE> Manila to Hold Formal Peace Talks With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Monday that it was "highly optimistic" about opening formal peace
talks with the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) this
September.
</P>
<P>
Orlando Mercado, secretary of the Department of National
Defense, said negotiators from both sides are now finalizing
discussions on the identification of MILF camps in Mindanao island
as part of the agenda of the talks.
</P>
<P>
"The tentative schedule for opening the peace talks is in
September. We expect everything to go smoothly, and we hope this
process will continue," Mercado said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
At present, he said, the identification of MILF camps appears
to be the only "problematic area" being threshed out by the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
But he expressed confidence that government negotiators can
resolve the issue in time for the opening of formal peace
negotiations next month.
</P>
<P>
"They are discussing problematic areas now. These particular
camps ostensibly are the ones where the forces of the MILF are,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MILF started exploratory negotiations in
late 1996 after the government forged a formal peace agreement
with the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF), another major
rebel group in the country.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada has thrown his full support
behind the peace efforts, but made it clear that the government
will strictly abide by the constitution in entering into
negotiations with the secessionist group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
