<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rapid Development In China's Advertising Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- China's advertisers did 5.3
billion U.S. dollars worth of business in 1998, a 45 percent
increase from 1997, in spite of the Asian financial meltdown,
according to an AC Nielsen survey.
</P>
<P>
China has become the second largest advertising market in the
Asian and Pacific region, after Japan, but, because of last year's
financial turmoil, business with the Republic of Korea, Thailand,
Malaysia was down around 20 percent, and with Singapore, about 7
percent.
</P>
<P>
A Nielsen analyst attributes the growth of Chinese advertising
business to expanded coverage and increased investment.
</P>
<P>
Taiwanese advertisers also reported rapid growth last year,
with income from TV and newspaper advertisements alone worth 2.5
billion dollars, an increase of 19 percent. Hong Kong's
advertisers saw a 2 percent increase to 2.7 billion dollars worth.
</P>
<P>
AC Nielsen is a leading international company specializing in
market surveys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
