<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Arctic Expedition Finishes Research in Bering Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, August 2 (Xinhua) -- With China's first
Arctic expedition completing a 12-day oceanic research in Bering
Sea early this morning, the Snow Dragon ship is sailing northward
to the Arctic Ocean for the next stage of investigation.
</P>
<P>
The survey in Bering Sea covered nearly 240,000 square
kilometers, including six sections and 42 station sites.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have carried out physical detection,
chemical, geological, isotopes, atmosphere, and carbon dioxide
sampling. They also collected plankton and studied fishery
resources in this region.
</P>
<P>
Qin Weijia, an assistant to the chief scientist, described the
research as very "successful", and said that it will help enrich
the knowledge of Chinese scientists about marine resources in
Bering Sea.
</P>
<P>
This is the first comprehensive marine survey China has ever
done in this sea area since the dawn of history, he said, adding
that "the research on the exchange of water flows between the
Arctic Ocean and North Pacific Ocean may provide sufficient data
to the study of environmental effect and climate changes."
</P>
<P>
Success of the research showed that Chinese scientists had made
great progress in oceanic study since the beginning of China's
reform and opening-up two decades ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
