<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fishing Ban in South China Sea Lifted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Amid cracking of fireworks,
fishermen of Panyu in south China's Guangzhou City set sail for
ocean fishing from a dock at the estuary of the Pearl River at
midnight Saturday when the first fishing ban imposed on the South
China Sea area was lifted.
</P>
<P>
Judging from the first catch after the ban, Captain Li Weixiong
said that the catches in the coming weeks will be up 20 percent
over the same period last year. Li made a catch of some 2,000 kg
of fish in his boat's first catch yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The fish catch and income of Chinese farmers have been
decreasing in the past years. The Ministry of Agriculture
introduced the fishing ban in a hope to foster and rationally use
fishing resources, and ensure a sustainable growth of ocean
fishery, so as to protect the fishermen's long-term benefits.
</P>
<P>
The fishing ban, which started on June 1, involved more than 30,
000 boats and one million fishermen, including some 1,800 boats
from Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
In the past two months, only 0.41 per thousand of the fishing
vessels were found fishing illegally in the South China Sea,
according to an official who is in charge of the fishing ban in
the area.
</P>
<P>
The government has subsidized those fishermen who are in need
as a result of the fishing ban, the official said, adding that the
supply and prices of seafood remained stable during the period due
to the adequate store of seafood and pelagic fishing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
