<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: E.Asia's Tourism Recovering From Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- After being severely hit by a
financial crisis, East Asia's tourism industry is beginning to
pick up, and the pace is expected to grow faster in the months
ahead with the regional economy continuously turning around.
</P>
<P>
As a major foreign exchange earner, the tourism industry
accounted for 10.3 percent of East Asian nations' gross domestic
product in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
However, since 70 percent of tourists come from within the
region, the outbreak of a regional financial crisis in mid-1997
affected badly the tourism industry in East Asia. The rising
commodity prices, the higher unemployment rate and the lower
living standard as a result of currency devaluations forced people
to cancel their travels abroad.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest report by the World Tourism
Organization, the economic crisis reduced the number of tourist
arrivals in East Asia by 1.2 percent to 87 million in 1998, with
the region's tourism receipts down by 3.8 percent to 74 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But since the beginning of this year, East Asia's economic
turnaround has prompted the recovery of the tourism industry. In
the crisis-hit East Asian countries, tourist arrivals rose
significantly.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, visitor arrivals grew by 17.9 percent year on
year in June, the biggest jump so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures from the Singapore Tourism Board show that
574,800 visitors came to Singapore in June, bringing the total
number of visitor arrivals in the first half of this year to 3.33
million, up 8.9 percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, tourist arrivals grew by 10 percent to 2.566
million in the first five months due to the economic recovery,
said the Tourism Authority of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, according to the authority, remained one of the most
favorite destinations for South Koreans with 125,719 tourists
visiting Thailand in the first half of this year, a surge of 122
percent compared to the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, visitor receipts in the first half of the
year also were up by 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, some analysts said, the industry's recovery
should not only be attributed to the brighter economic picture,
but also to promotion activities and a great stimulus by East
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Such an assessment seems to be reasonable. For example, the
"Amazing Thailand" campaign in the past two years has proved the
success of Thailand's tourism marketing strategy, which helped the
country become the first in Asia to show a recovery in the number
of foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the government invested 222 million pesos
(5.85 million dollars) in improving 12 tourism projects in the
first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
But East Asian countries are not satisfied with the growing
number of tourist arrivals, and they are trying in one way and
another to attract more foreign travelers.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is willing to relax its travel and visa requirements
to accommodate the needs of foreign tourists, Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohammed said recently.
</P>
<P>
"We are very keen to have people stay a longer time in Malaysia
and for that we prepared to relax our visa requirements," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government would try to accommodate as much as possible the
needs of visitors including the South Korean tourists, as their
country had registered very rapid recovery after the financial
crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the tourism department launched a
"Re-discovering the Philippines" campaign months ago, appealing to
the third and fourth generations of Filipinos abroad to come back
and "find their roots."
</P>
<P>
A Philippine mission left here Sunday for a two-week tour of
four major U.S. cities -- Los Angeles, San Francisco, Chicago and
New York -- for promotion activities. They will offer tourists
lower rates for accommodations and travelling in their country.
</P>
<P>
With new marketing strategies and a recovering regional
economy, East Asian countries are optimistic about the growth in
the tourism industry this year.
</P>
<P>
The Tourism Authority of Thailand forecast 8.28 million tourist
arrivals for Thailand this year, compared to 7.7 million in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
