<HEADLINE> 10 Killed in Manila Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Flash floods hit the Philippine
capital of Manila Sunday night, killing 10 people, including a
family of seven in a landslide, an official report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report by the Office of Civil Defense (OCD)
here, the seven who died in a landslide were from one family in
the Cainta area of the capital, and three others were apparently
swept by rampaging waters.
</P>
<P>
The family was inside their house when the landslide struck,
burying them alive, the OCD said.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains, which authorities claimed were brought about
by the much-feared La Nina phenomenon, continued to pelt Manila
and nearby provinces during the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The OCD said flood waters in some areas of the city were 17.9
meters deep after days of big rains.
</P>
<P>
Many areas in the metropolis and nearby provinces have remained
underwater as of Monday morning, it said.
</P>
<P>
Floodwaters have reached roof-deep in some parts of Marikina
and Cainta, and the OCD has deployed amphibious vehicles and
trucks to rescue stranded residents.
</P>
<P>
The OCD said that hundreds of people had to climb to the
rooftop of their houses because of the rising floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
Rescue operations are now in full swing, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
