<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Aids S.Lanka's Coastal Environment Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka and Australia have
signed a Memorandum of Understanding for a coastal zone waste
management project in the south, the Ministry of Finance said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The project costing 279 million rupees (4 million U.S. dollars)
aims to improve the environment of Hikkaduwa, a holiday resort
town 100 kilometers south of Colombo, the ministry said in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
Australia will provide a grant of about 107 million rupees
(1.53 million dollars) through the Australian Agency International
Development (AusAID).
</P>
<P>
The grant will be provided through technical, personnel,
training and study tours, equipment and civil works for the solid
waste facility, and community programs, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government will contribute 172 million rupees
(2.47 million dollars) primarily through provision of land for the
sewerage system and the solid waste facility.
</P>
<P>
The three-year project will introduce environmentally friendly
solid and liquid waste management systems and help reduce the
adverse environmental impact of sewage and solid waste disposal.
</P>
<P>
The project will focus on community assistance providing
opportunity for income generation and health benefits to the
poorer sections of the community.
</P>
<P>
It will also form an integral part of Sri Lanka's national
plans for environment improvement and protection with specific
emphasis on coastal zones, the release noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
