<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Riot Have No Impact on Foreign Investment in Indonesia' Batam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The recent rioting in Batam,
Indonesia, has had no impact on the interests of foreign investors
in developing their businesses in the area, head of the Batam
Authority Area Ismeth Abdullah said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said there were no foreign investors who cancelled their
business activities. In fact, several investors have built new
factories with the total investment at 26 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed optimism that the foreign investment in Batam
could reach 60 million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
He also said Batam has a strategic position for various
industries and is close to Malaysia and Singapore for the market
destination.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, the low-cost labor here (Batam) is also one of
the elements attracting foreign investors," he was quoted by the
Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Batam, just 35 km southeast of Singapore, is a special
industrial zone and also a popular tourist destination for
Singaporeans.
</P>
<P>
Batam now has 370 foreign industrial factories which have
absorbed 1.6 million employees, and for the next five years, the
area is projected to receive investment of 15 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Violent clashes between migrant groups from Sumatera and Flores
in Batam since Thursday have claimed at least 13 lives. The
clashes occurred following a dispute over parking lots between two
individuals from the two groups.
</P>
<P>
According to Antara News Agency, the situation in Batam island
is now stable and under control, as the communal clashes there
ended following the signing of a peace agreement between the two
migrant communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
