<HEADLINE> China's Major Oil Company Needs More Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- China National Petroleum (Group)
Corp (CNPC) will further solicit overseas capital for some
projects regarding oil exploration, refining and pipe laying.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for CNPC was quoted by Monday's China Daily as
saying that the company is carrying out project appraisals and
conducting negotiations with foreign counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The CNPC has been stressing the exploration of natural gas in
central China, looking for rich oil reserves in east China, and
trying to achieve significant discoveries when prospecting in west
China.
</P>
<P>
It has designated 24 oil refining facilities for technical
upgrading this year, and will complete the upgrading of some
reforming units and hydroprocessing lubricating oil and diesel
hydrogenating facilities, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, CNPC produced 53.4 million tons
of crude oil, an increase of 351,000 tons over the same 1998
period, and processed 35.5 million tons of crude oil. Production
of natural gas surged 10 percent year-on-year to hit eight billion
cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Sales revenues in the period totaled 164.3 billion yuan (about
19.8 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Since June this year, CNPC has taken forceful measures to
streamline its operations and establish a management system in
line with international standards. Its five subsidiaries have
begun to implement their restructuring plans, too. As many as 49
enterprises operating under CNPC are following suit to reorganize
their corporate structures, according to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Current Account Deficit Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Despite a well-performed
economy, Australians are deeply concerned over the country's
growing current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released recently, Australia's current
account deficit in 1998-99 stood at around 22.44 billion U.S.
dollars compared with 15.51 billion U.S. dollars in the previous
financial year. The figure for 1996-97 was about 11.88 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review said on Monday that the main
reason was the apparently increasing participation of foreign
investors in the Australian bond and stock markets.
</P>
<P>
It asked people to look at the earlier success of the
intriguing economic experiment in New Zealand in the late 1980s
and early 1990s, to see how huge foreign participation in an
economy can work to undermine it.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand's economy was once at the top of the Organization
for Economic Cooperation and Development in terms of high growth,
low inflation and strong international investor confidence, and it
resulted in a significant rise of foreign ownership of it's bonds
and stocks which reached to about two thirds of the market.
</P>
<P>
The paper said it was the high current account deficit that
forced the NZ dollar to plummet, and as a result, New Zealand fell
into a sharp recession.
</P>
<P>
The lessons from that experience should be salutary for palicy
makers and financial markets in Australia, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Australian officials has stressed repeatedly in recent months
that the Australian economy has entered into the fast lane with
it's high growth rate of nearly 5 percent and low inflation of
under 1.5 percent as well as the lowest interest rate for 30
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
