<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Flee S.Lankan Rebels-Held Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Several thousand Sri Lankan
civilians have fled the Tamil rebels-held Wanni in the country's
north, as the rebels and the army are locked in a dispute over a
safe land route for civilians in the area.
</P>
<P>
Over 3,000 civilians have sought refuge in the Mannar security
zone in Sri Lanka's northwest and have been accommodated at the
Pesalai refugee camp, said reports reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The refugees, who are receiving a better deal at the hands of
the government, are now condemning the Tamil rebels for killing
members of their own Tamil community, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The army and the Tamil rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) have been discussing a new safe land route between
Wanni and government-controlled areas for transport of food as
well as movement of civilians.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have rejected the army's offer to set up a
"civilian safety zone" for fears the army could mount fresh
offensives against them.
</P>
<P>
The government has traditionally supplied food and other items
to civilians in rebel-held areas, while allowing them access to
government-controlled towns for trade and other activities.
</P>
<P>
An earlier route was closed in May when the army launched a
fresh offensive in its war against the Tamil rebels, who have been
fighting for a separate homeland in Sri Lanka's north and east for
minority Tamils since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
