<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Updated) Canadian Tests Positive for Banned Substance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Canada was stripped of
its Pan Am Games roller hockey gold medal here on Sunday after
goalkeeper Steve Vezina tested positive for two stimulants and an
anabolic steroid.
</P>
<P>
The gold now goes to the United States, the silver to Argentina
and the bronze to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
"Steve Vezina gave a positive result...we decided to withdraw
the gold medal from the winning team, Canada. We regret to do so
but we have to follow the rules." Mario Vazquez Rana, president of
the Pan American Sports Organization, said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
Canada defeated the Americans 7-6 for the Games gold in a
thrilling
final last Tuesday. Vezina's goaltending was credited as a key
part of the victory.
</P>
<P>
Vezina was the lone Canadian roller hockey player tested
positive. Eduardo de Rose, the chief of the Games Medical
Commission, said Vezina's sample showed an excessively high level
of the steroid Nandrolone--16,000 parts per million compared to
the acceptable level of two parts per million.
</P>
<P>
"This is a lot of steroids, this is not normal," Rose said.
</P>
<P>
Vezina, 24, plays a professional roller hockey for the Buffalo
Wings.
</P>
<P>
The drug test showed three banned substances--ephedrine, pseudo-
ephedrine and Nandrolone. The former two are stimulants used to
avoid fatigue and Nandrolone is an anabolic steroid that increases
muscle mass.
</P>
<P>
The officials said there were no medical reasons for the drugs.
</P>
<P>
The positive test is the lastest in a line of black eyes for
Canadian athletes on the international stage.
</P>
<P>
Snowboarder Ross Rebagliati tested positive for marijuana at
the 1998 Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan and was stripped of his
gold medal in the giant slalom. His medal was restored after the
Canadian team successfully appealed, arguing it was not a
performance-enhancing drug.
</P>
<P>
Rower Silken Laumann tested positive for a banned stimulant at
the 1995 Pan Am Games in Mar Del Plata, Argentina after taking the
wrong over-the-counter cold medicine. The positive drug test cost
her and her quad-sculls teammates their gold medals.
</P>
<P>
And Ben Johnson put doping on the map with his positive test at
the 1988 Seoul Olympics.
</P>
<P>
About six Pan Am athletes have tested positive at each Games
over the past 20 years, except at Caracas in 198, when 19 tested
positive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
