<HEADLINE> Doping Incident Overshadows Pan Am Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Doping phantom surfaced
at the 13th Pan Am Games here today when one member of the
Canadian men's gold-winning roller hockey team failed a drug test.
</P>
<P>
Canada was stripped of its Pan Am gold medal Sunday after
goalkeeper Steve Vezina tested positive for two stimulants and an
anabolic steroid.
</P>
<P>
The gold now goes to the United States, the silver to Argentina
and the bronze to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Canada defeated the Americans 7-6 for the Games gold in a
thrilling
final last Tuesday. Vezina's goaltending was credited as a key
part of the victory.
</P>
<P>
Eduardo de Rose, the chief of the Games Medical Commission,
said Vezina's sample showed an excessively high level of the
steroid Nandrolone--16,000 parts per million compared to the
acceptable level of two parts per million.
</P>
<P>
The doping incident even more overshadowed a relatively
uneventful day whose sole highlight was Brazil beating Cuba for
women's volleyball gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Brazil came from one set down to score a 20-25, 25-22, 25-27,
25-22, 15-13 thrilling victory over their mighty opponents Cuba,
who were the defending Olympic and world champions.
</P>
<P>
In the baseball competition, Canada's amazing victorious stream
finally snapped when Cuba avenged a disgraceful group match defeat
by beating the host nation 3-2.
</P>
<P>
The other semi-final will be between the United States and
Mexico later today with an Olympic berth at stake. The top two
finishers at the Games qualify for the 2000 Olympics in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The United States still tops the medals table with 70 golds, 62
silvers and 41 bronzes, with Cuba and Canada second and third, on
33 and 30 golds respectively. Argentina placed fourth with 20
golds, followed by Brazil who has collected 10 golds. 
</P>
