<HEADLINE> Bryan Twins Advance to Double Semi-finals at Pan Am </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Identical twins Bob and
Mike Bryan of the United States advanced into the medal round of
the Pan Am Games tennis competitions Sunday with a 6-2, 6-1
victory over Simon Evelyn and Shane Stone of Trinidad and Togago.
</P>
<P>
In the semi-finals, the duo will face the winner of the match
between the team of Guillermo Coria and David Nalbanian of
Argentina and the team of Oscar Ortiz and Marco Osorio of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
"We're not here to get any medal other than gold," said Mike
Bryan.
</P>
<P>
"We'll be upset if we don't win the gold here," said Bob Bryan.
"That's what we came here for. We want the gold, bad."
</P>
<P>
In their two doubles matches at the Pan Am Games, the Bryans
have not lost a set or lost a service game. With two more
victories, the Bryans would become the first U.S. doubles team to
win the gold medal at the Pan Am Games since Luke Jensen and
Patrick McEnroe won the gold medal at the 1987 Pan Am Games in
Indianapolis, the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We have a couple more matches to go," said US coach Scott
McCain. "We got to take it one match at a time. We are not looking
passed anybody."
</P>
<P>
The Bryans are currently the No.13 ranked doubles team in the
ATP Tour doubles team rankings. Although the duo have yet to
represent the United States in Davis Cup play, they see their Pan
Am experience as a step in that direction and ultimately toward a
possible selection to the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney. 
</P>
</TEXT>
