<HEADLINE> Canada Stripped of Gold due to Doping Offense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian roller
hockey team was stripped of the gold they won on July 27 after one
of its member was tested positive for steroid, the Pan Ammerican
Sports Organization (PASO) announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The doping tests of Steve Vezina resulted positive on both the
A and B samples.
</P>
<P>
In accordance to the Pan American Games Regulations, the PASO
Executive Committee decided to withdraw the gold medal from the
Canadian Team, who will have to hand them back openly to the
United States. The silver medal consequently went to Argentina and
the bronze medal to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
There were three different prohibited substances found in
Vezina's urine samples and the quantity was "very high", said
Eduardo de Rose, chairman of the PASO medical commission.
</P>
<P>
The materials were mainly used to help athletes recover from
fatigue and increase their body power, Rose said.
</P>
<P>
After their 7-6 narrow victory over the United States in the
men's roller hockey final four days ago, eight members of the
Canadian team received doping tests.
</P>
<P>
Vezina, a 24-year-old profession, is now unavailable for any
comments and subject to sanctions from the International Hockey
Federation.
</P>
<P>
Don Mackenzie, president of the Winnipeg Games Organizatoin
Committee, said they were hugely disappointed and deeply regretful
about the doping offense.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged the media to focus on the sports itself and the
outstanding performances of the Pan Am athletes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
