<BODY>
<HEADLINE> End Finally in Sight to Anelka Saga </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Asrenal football club manager
Arsena Wenger finally said goodbye to Nicolas Anelka and hello
again to the FA Charity Shield after Arsenal beat Manchester
United 2-1 at Wembley on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Gunners' success was overshadowed by the news that they had
agreed the 22 million pounds sale of rebel striker Anelka to Real
Madrid. Wenger confirmed that Anelka's move to Spain is complete,
barring the final signatures on the contract and a routine medical
examination which should be done within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
And although Arsenal have had to sacrifice a principle in
selling him to the Spanish giants whom they had formally accused
of illegal poaching of the player just two months ago, the Gunners
boss admitted: "It is the best thing for everybody that it is all
over."
</P>
<P>
He added: "We have had an explanation from Real Madrid that has
satisfied the club. I wanted to keep the player and I'm
disappointed we could not sit down together and talk but in the
end he wants to go.
</P>
<P>
"We have decided to let him join Real Madrid because the
transfer figure is a reasonable one and we don't want to be
responsible for killing the boy's career.
</P>
<P>
"It is a story that has lasted all summer and has always been
on a knife-edge. This club (Arsenal) would have survived if he had
not played but I'm not sure Anelka could have.
</P>
<P>
"Now we must forget all this and concentrate on the season
ahead. And that performance today showed we still have the right
spirit and don't have to depend on one man."
</P>
<P>
Anelka had originally claimed that Real Madrid were the only
club he wanted to join when he turned his back on Arsenal at the
end of last season despite having four years of his Highbury
contract still to run. But when the Gunners at first refused to
deal with the Spaniards, Lazio came on to the scene and one of the
most tedious transfer stories for years began to unfold. Finally,
the Italians pulled out, claiming that Arsenal's 22 million pounds
asking price was too high.
</P>
<P>
Now Real, despite massive debts, are believed to be raising the
money to buy the 20-year-old French international from a lucrative
Spanish television deal.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal vice chairman David Dein said: "It is a done deal
subject to Nicolas passing a medical. We've got to get on with our
lives. It has been a long and unpleasant saga." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
