<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Positive Test Strips Canada of Gold Medal (updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The gold medal for the
men's roller hockey champions was re-awarded today to the United
States after one member of the initial winners Canada failed a
drug test.
</P>
<P>
Canadian goalie Steve Vezina tested positive for three banned
substances, following the July 27 final against the United States,
over which Canada scored a narrow 7-6 victory.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Pan American Sports Organization (PASO)
regulations, the Executive Committee of PASO decided to strip the
gold medal of the entire Canadian team and give them to the United
States, and consequently hand the silver to Argentina and the
bronze to the original fourth-place finisher Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Two of the banned substances, pseudoephedrine and ephedrine,
are nervous system stimulants that assist in overcoming fatigue,
according to PASP Chief Medical Officer Eduardo de Rose. The third
substance, nandrolone, is an anabolic steroid used to increase
muscle mass.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Olympic Association (COA) has sent a letter to the
PASO Medical Commission which stated there would be no dispute
over the positive test results.
</P>
<P>
The COA announced here today they deeply regret the incident
and the impact it has had on the sport of roller hockey and the
image of the Winnipeg Pan Am Games.
</P>
<P>
They insisted that the COA remains committed to drug-free
sports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
