<DOCNO> XIE19990802.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bailey Satisfied with Silver Performances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Former men's 100m world
record holder Donovan Bailey said here today he was satisfied with
the silver he won with the Canadian 4X100m relay team.
</P>
<P>
The defending Olympic champion blew out of the starting blocks
to give Canadian team a lightening-fast lead but anchor man
Trevino Betty couldn't catch up to Brazil as Canada had to settle
for silver last night at the University of Manitoba Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Bailey wrapped up a turbulent week in Winnipeg by doing what he
does best -- running faster with Glenroy Gilbert, Brad McCuaig and
Betty as a sellout crowd of close to 11,000 widely cheered them on.
</P>
<P>
"I knew I had a decent start when I passed both guys and handed
off to Glenroy, " Bailey said. "This is a stepping stone to the
world championships."
</P>
<P>
"We're running out of position, but it's OK. Maybe if I
anchored, it would have been different, maybe if Trevino led off
it would have been different. Who knows?
</P>
<P>
"But we're going to be just fine. We can't sit and worry about
one race. It's over now. There are bigger things this year."
</P>
<P>
It is over now for Bailey, as far as Winnipeg's concerned.
</P>
<P>
Bailey, whose record of 9.84 was squeezed down by American
Maurice Greene to 9.79 in June, refused an offer by Athletics
Canada to run the 100m because he wasn't asked initially.
</P>
<P>
The Pan Am Games poster boy, who was paid more than 200,000
Canadian dollars to promote the Games, also failed to show up in
the opening ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
But he insisted he did the right thing, and pointed to the
crowd's roaring approval of all four members of the Canadian team
as proof.
</P>
<P>
"I was always committed to the Games and I said I would come
here and do a good job and I did," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
